VALUES (
  'Achalasia - LHM vs POEM',
  'surgery-esophagus-achalasia-lhm-vs-poem',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# Achalasia - LHM vs POEM: Current Evidence\n\n## Overview\n\nAchalasia treatment has evolved significantly with the introduction of Per-Oral Endoscopic Myotomy (POEM) in 2010. This topic compares the two definitive surgical approaches: Laparoscopic Heller Myotomy (LHM) with fundoplication versus POEM, examining the current evidence to guide treatment selection.\n\n```\nEVOLUTION OF ACHALASIA TREATMENT\n════════════════════════════════\n\n1913: Heller - Original open cardiomyotomy (anterior + posterior)\n       │\n1962: Modified to single (anterior) myotomy\n       │\n1991: First Laparoscopic Heller Myotomy (LHM)\n       │         └── Added partial fundoplication\n       │\n2010: Inoue - First POEM in humans (Japan)\n       │\n2020s: LHM vs POEM trials emerge\n       │\nToday: Both are first-line options for Types I/II\n       POEM preferred for Type III\n```\n\n---\n\n## Laparoscopic Heller Myotomy (LHM)\n\n### Surgical Technique\n\n```\nLHM WITH DOR FUNDOPLICATION\n════════════════════════════\n\nPosition: Supine, split-leg, reverse Trendelenburg\n\nPort Placement:\n     ┌─────────────────────┐\n     │         ○ (10mm)    │  ← Camera\n     │        /│\\          │\n     │       / │ \\         │\n     │      ○  │  ○        │  ← Working ports (5mm)\n     │     /   │   \\       │\n     │    ○    │    ○      │  ← Assistant/Liver retractor\n     │         │           │\n     └─────────────────────┘\n\nKey Steps:\n1. Divide gastrohepatic ligament\n2. Identify EGJ and crura\n3. Clear fat pad at EGJ\n4. Create myotomy window\n5. Myotomy: 6 cm esophageal + 2-3 cm gastric\n6. Verify complete (mucosal bulge)\n7. Partial fundoplication (Dor or Toupet)\n```\n\n### Myotomy Details\n\n```\nMYOTOMY ANATOMY\n═══════════════\n\n                    Proximal\n                       ↑\n                       │\n    ┌──────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                                   │\n    │   ════════════════════════       │  Outer longitudinal\n    │                                   │\n    │   ▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓        │  Circular muscle\n    │   ▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓        │  (DIVIDE THIS)\n    │                                   │\n    │   ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░    │  Mucosa\n    │                                   │  (PRESERVE)\n    │   ════════════════════════       │\n    │   ▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓        │\n    │   ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░    │\n    │                                   │\n    └──────────────────────────────────┘\n                       │\n                       ↓\n        ├───── 6 cm ─────┤───── 2-3 cm ────┤\n           Esophageal         Gastric\n           (above EGJ)        (below EGJ)\n\nTotal myotomy length: 8-9 cm\n```\n\n### Fundoplication Options\n\n| Type | Wrap Degree | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|------|-------------|------------|---------------|\n| **Dor (Anterior)** | 180° anterior | Covers myotomy, easier | Less anti-reflux |\n| **Toupet (Posterior)** | 270° posterior | Better anti-reflux, keeps edges apart | Doesn''t cover myotomy |\n| **None** | 0° | Shorter, simpler | Higher GERD rates |\n\n```\nDOR vs TOUPET FUNDOPLICATION\n════════════════════════════\n\nDOR (180° Anterior):                TOUPET (270° Posterior):\n\n    Esophagus                           Esophagus\n        │                                   │\n   ┌────┴────┐                         ┌────┴────┐\n   │ ←Fundus │                         │         │\n   │   wrap  │                     wrap│    wrap │\n   └─────────┘                    ←────┘    ────→│\n        │                                   │\n    Stomach                             Stomach\n\n• Covers myotomy site              • Keeps myotomy edges apart\n• Protects if leak                 • Better anti-reflux effect\n• Easier technically               • Does not cover myotomy\n```\n\n**Consensus:** Dor is most commonly used for achalasia (covers myotomy)\n\n---\n\n## Per-Oral Endoscopic Myotomy (POEM)\n\n### Technique Overview\n\n```\nPOEM PROCEDURE - STEP BY STEP\n══════════════════════════════\n\nStep 1: Mucosal Incision (10-12 cm above EGJ)\n        ┌─────────────────┐\n        │   ═══════       │  ← Mucosal incision\n        │   │             │     (longitudinal)\n        │   │             │\n        │   │ Tunnel      │\n        │   ↓             │\n        │                 │\n        │      EGJ        │\n        └─────────────────┘\n\nStep 2: Submucosal Tunnel\n        ┌─────────────────┐\n        │   ═══════       │  Entry\n        │   │░░░░░│       │\n        │   │░░░░░│       │  Submucosal space\n        │   │░░░░░│       │  (blue dye injection)\n        │   │░░░░░│       │\n        │   │░░░░░│       │\n        │   ↓     ↓       │\n        │   2 cm below EGJ│\n        └─────────────────┘\n\nStep 3: Myotomy (Selective Circular)\n        ┌─────────────────┐\n        │   Mucosa intact │\n        │   │     │       │\n        │   │XXXXX│       │  Circular muscle divided\n        │   │XXXXX│       │  (in tunnel)\n        │   │XXXXX│       │\n        │   │XXXXX│       │\n        │   ↓XXXXX↓       │\n        │   Past EGJ      │\n        └─────────────────┘\n\nStep 4: Closure\n        ┌─────────────────┐\n        │   ○○○○○○○       │  ← Clips to close\n        │                 │     mucosal entry\n        │   Tunnel sealed │\n        │                 │\n        └─────────────────┘\n```\n\n### POEM Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Standard Approach |\n|-----------|-------------------|\n| Entry point | 10-12 cm above EGJ |\n| Tunnel length | Entry to 2-3 cm past EGJ |\n| Myotomy start | 2-3 cm below mucosal entry |\n| Myotomy extent | 2-3 cm onto gastric cardia |\n| Total myotomy | 10-12 cm (can extend for Type III) |\n| Approach | Posterior (5-6 o''clock) or Anterior (2 o''clock) |\n| Closure | Endoscopic clips or suturing |\n\n### Extended Myotomy for Type III\n\n```\nPOEM ADVANTAGE IN TYPE III ACHALASIA\n════════════════════════════════════\n\nStandard LHM:                    POEM:\n\n    ╔════════════════╗           ╔════════════════╗\n    ║                ║           ║   XXXXXXXXX    ║\n    ║                ║           ║   XXXXXXXXX    ║ Extended\n    ║                ║           ║   XXXXXXXXX    ║ myotomy\n    ║    ╔════════╗  ║           ║   XXXXXXXXX    ║ (proximal)\n    ║    ║XXXXXXXX║  ║           ║   XXXXXXXXX    ║\n    ║    ║XXXXXXXX║  ║           ║   XXXXXXXXX    ║\n    ║    ║XXXXXXXX║  ║           ║   XXXXXXXXX    ║\n    ╚════║XXXXXXXX║══╝           ║   XXXXXXXXX    ║\n         ║XXXXXXXX║              ║   XXXXXXXXX    ║\n         ║XXXXXXXX║              ║   XXXXXXXXX    ║\n         ╚════════╝              ╚════════════════╝\n\n    Max 6-8 cm                   Can reach 15+ cm\n    Limited by surgical         Limited only by\n    exposure                    scope length\n\nType III has spastic contractions proximally\n→ POEM can address these with extended myotomy\n```\n\n---\n\n## Head-to-Head Comparison\n\n### Key Randomized Controlled Trials\n\n#### 1. Werner et al. (2019) - European Multicenter RCT\n\n| Parameter | POEM (n=112) | LHM+Dor (n=109) | P-value |\n|-----------|--------------|-----------------|---------|\n| 2-year success (Eckardt ≤3) | 83% | 81.7% | 0.007 (non-inferior) |\n| Reflux esophagitis | 44% | 29% | 0.02 |\n| Procedure time | 103 min | 146 min | <0.001 |\n| Hospital stay | 3 days | 3 days | NS |\n| Serious AE | 2.7% | 7.3% | NS |\n\n#### 2. Ponds et al. (2019) - Dutch RCT\n\n| Parameter | POEM (n=60) | PD (n=66) | P-value |\n|-----------|-------------|-----------|---------|\n| 2-year success | 92% | 54% | <0.001 |\n| Reflux esophagitis | 41% | 7% | <0.001 |\n| Re-intervention | 0% | 16% | 0.001 |\n\n#### 3. Multiple Meta-analyses (2020-2024)\n\n```\nMETA-ANALYSIS SUMMARY\n═════════════════════\n\n                    POEM          LHM\n                    ────          ───\nEfficacy           ████████████   ████████████\n(Eckardt ≤3)       91-93%        89-91%\n\nDysphagia          ████████████   ████████████\nResolution         95-97%        94-96%\n\nGERD               █████████░░░   ██████░░░░░░\n                   35-45%        15-25%\n\nMucosal            ███░░░░░░░░░   █░░░░░░░░░░░\nPerforation        2-5%          <1%\n\nRe-intervention    ██░░░░░░░░░░   ███░░░░░░░░░\n                   3-5%          5-8%\n\nLength of Stay     ██░░░░░░░░░░   ███░░░░░░░░░\n                   1-2 days      1-3 days\n```\n\n### Comparative Summary Table\n\n| Factor | LHM + Fundoplication | POEM | Winner |\n|--------|---------------------|------|--------|\n| **Short-term efficacy** | 90-95% | 90-95% | Tie |\n| **Long-term efficacy (5yr)** | 85-90% | 80-90% | LHM (slightly) |\n| **GERD rate** | 10-25% | 35-50% | LHM |\n| **Barrett''s risk** | Lower | Higher | LHM |\n| **Type III achalasia** | 60-70% | 85-95% | POEM |\n| **Procedure time** | Longer | Shorter | POEM |\n| **Hospital stay** | 1-3 days | 1-2 days | POEM |\n| **Repeat procedure** | More difficult | Possible | POEM |\n| **Prior treatment failure** | Less effective | Effective | POEM |\n| **Learning curve** | Established | Steep | LHM |\n| **External incisions** | Yes (5 ports) | No | POEM |\n| **Fundoplication** | Included | None | LHM |\n\n---\n\n## GERD After Myotomy\n\n### The GERD Problem\n\n```\nPATHOPHYSIOLOGY OF POST-MYOTOMY GERD\n════════════════════════════════════\n\nNormal EGJ Competence:           After Myotomy:\n\n    ────────────                     ────────────\n        │                                │\n    ╔═══╧═══╗ LES tone              ╔═══╧═══╗ LES disrupted\n    ║       ║                       ║ X X X ║\n    ╚═══╤═══╝                       ╚═══╤═══╝\n        │                                │\n    ════╪════ Diaphragm             ════╪════ May still anchor\n        │                                │\n        ▼                                ▼\n\n    Anti-reflux mechanisms:         Residual protection:\n    1. LES intrinsic tone ✗        1. Diaphragm\n    2. His angle                    2. His angle\n    3. Phrenoesophageal lig.       3. Gravity\n    4. Diaphragm                    4. Saliva clearance\n\n    Fundoplication restores:        POEM: No wrap\n    - Wrap acts as flap valve       - Higher GERD rates\n    - Augments competence           - Needs PPI long-term\n```\n\n### GERD Rates Comparison\n\n| Measure | LHM + Dor | POEM | Significance |\n|---------|-----------|------|--------------|\n| Reflux symptoms | 10-20% | 20-30% | Higher with POEM |\n| Erosive esophagitis | 15-25% | 35-50% | Significantly higher |\n| Pathological acid exposure | 20-30% | 40-60% | Higher with POEM |\n| Barrett''s esophagus | <5% | 5-10% | May be higher |\n| PPI requirement | 20-30% | 50-70% | Higher with POEM |\n\n### Managing Post-POEM GERD\n\n```\nPOST-POEM REFLUX MANAGEMENT\n═══════════════════════════\n\nAll POEM Patients:\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ 1. PPI prophylaxis (6-12 months minimum)   │\n│ 2. Lifestyle modifications                  │\n│ 3. Annual or biennial EGD surveillance     │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n            │\n            ▼\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ Symptomatic GERD develops                   │\n│                                             │\n│ • Continue/optimize PPI                    │\n│ • Confirm on pH monitoring if needed       │\n│ • Consider laparoscopic fundoplication     │\n│   if PPI-refractory                        │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nFuture Option:\nPOEM + Fundoplication (POEM-F) being studied\n- Full-thickness myotomy + partial wrap\n- May reduce GERD rates\n- Currently investigational\n```\n\n---\n\n## Selection Algorithm\n\n### Patient Selection Framework\n\n```\nTREATMENT SELECTION ALGORITHM\n══════════════════════════════\n\n                    ACHALASIA CONFIRMED\n                           │\n           ┌───────────────┼───────────────┐\n           │               │               │\n       TYPE I          TYPE II         TYPE III\n           │               │               │\n           └───────┬───────┘               │\n                   │                       │\n                   ▼                       ▼\n        ┌──────────────────┐      ┌──────────────────┐\n        │ LHM, PD, or POEM │      │ POEM PREFERRED   │\n        │ (all equivalent)  │      │ (extended myotomy│\n        └────────┬─────────┘      │  capability)      │\n                 │                └──────────────────┘\n                 │\n    Consider patient factors:\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                                              │\n    │  Favor LHM if:          Favor POEM if:      │\n    │  ─────────────          ──────────────      │\n    │  • GERD concern         • No external cuts  │\n    │  • Young patient        • Prior failed tx   │\n    │  • Barrett''s risk       • Redo surgery risk │\n    │  • Hiatal hernia        • Shorter stay      │\n    │  • Surgeon expertise    • Type III          │\n    │                         • Endoscopist expert│\n    │                                              │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Specific Scenarios\n\n| Clinical Scenario | Preferred Approach | Rationale |\n|-------------------|-------------------|-----------|\n| Type I/II, young female | LHM + Dor | GERD/Barrett''s concern |\n| Type III achalasia | POEM | Extended myotomy needed |\n| Failed prior PD | POEM | Effective salvage |\n| Failed LHM | POEM | Easier redo than re-LHM |\n| Failed POEM | LHM | Can still perform |\n| Sigmoid esophagus | Either + consider Rx | May need esophagectomy |\n| Large hiatal hernia | LHM | Can repair hernia |\n| High surgical risk | POEM or Botox | Less invasive |\n| No GERD tolerance | LHM + Dor | Anti-reflux protection |\n\n---\n\n## Complications Comparison\n\n### Intraoperative\n\n| Complication | LHM | POEM | Management |\n|--------------|-----|------|------------|\n| Mucosal perforation | 1-3% | 3-8% | Clip/suture, usually heal |\n| Bleeding | <1% | 1-2% | Coagulation |\n| Pneumothorax | Rare | 1-2% | Chest tube if needed |\n| Pneumoperitoneum | N/A | Common | Usually resolves, needle decompression |\n| Incomplete myotomy | 2-5% | 2-5% | Re-intervention |\n\n### Postoperative\n\n```\nCOMPLICATION TIMELINE\n═════════════════════\n\nEARLY (Days 1-7):\n────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nLHM:                          POEM:\n• Wound infection (1-2%)      • Delayed leak (1-2%)\n• Leak from myotomy (rare)    • Subcutaneous emphysema\n• Bleeding                    • Fever (tunnel infection)\n• Gastroparesis               • Chest pain\n\nINTERMEDIATE (Weeks 1-6):\n────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nBoth:\n• Dysphagia (transient in 5-10%)\n• GERD symptoms emergence\n\nLATE (Months-Years):\n────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nLHM:                          POEM:\n• GERD (10-25%)               • GERD (35-50%)\n• Recurrent dysphagia (5-10%) • Recurrent dysphagia (5-10%)\n• Wrap migration/disruption   • Barrett''s esophagus\n• Incisional hernia (rare)    • No incision issues\n```\n\n---\n\n## Long-term Outcomes\n\n### Durability Data\n\n```\nLONG-TERM SUCCESS RATES\n═══════════════════════\n\n           1 yr    2 yr    5 yr    10 yr\n           ────    ────    ────    ─────\nLHM+Dor    94%     90%     85%     75-80%\n                    │\nPOEM       95%     90%     80-85%  Limited data\n                    │\n                    └──► Similar at 2 years\n                         LHM may have edge at 5+ years\n                         (pending more POEM long-term data)\n```\n\n### Factors Affecting Long-term Success\n\n| Factor | Impact | Notes |\n|--------|--------|-------|\n| Achalasia subtype | Type II best, Type III worst | Consistent across treatments |\n| Pre-op esophageal diameter | >6 cm = worse | Consider timing |\n| Myotomy completeness | Critical | Verify intraoperatively |\n| Fundoplication (LHM) | Prevents GERD | Dor most common |\n| Operator experience | High volume better | Learning curve matters |\n| Post-op compliance | PPI, surveillance | Affects outcomes |\n\n---\n\n## Special Considerations\n\n### Sigmoid Esophagus\n\n```\nSIGMOID ESOPHAGUS CLASSIFICATION\n════════════════════════════════\n\nGrade I (Mild):              Grade II (Severe):\n\n    │                            │\n    │ <6 cm                  ╭───╯\n    │                       ╭╯     >6 cm\n    └───                   ╭╯\n       │                  ╭╯\n       │                 ╰╮\n       ▼                  ╰╮\n                           ╰───▶\n\n• LHM/POEM effective        • Consider esophagectomy\n• 80-90% success            • High failure rate\n• Watch for progression     • If myotomy fails → Rx\n\nTreatment approach:\n1. Try LHM or POEM first\n2. If fails or progresses → Esophagectomy\n3. End-stage → Esophagectomy primary\n```\n\n### Prior Treatment History\n\n| Scenario | Recommendation |\n|----------|----------------|\n| Treatment-naïve | LHM, PD, or POEM |\n| Failed single PD | POEM or LHM |\n| Failed multiple PD | POEM (preferred) |\n| Failed LHM | POEM |\n| Failed POEM | LHM or re-POEM |\n| Failed both | Esophagectomy if end-stage |\n\n---\n\n## Key Evidence Summary\n\n### What the Evidence Shows\n\n```\n╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗\n║              CURRENT EVIDENCE CONCLUSIONS                   ║\n╠════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╣\n║                                                             ║\n║  1. EFFICACY: POEM ≈ LHM at 2 years (Level 1)             ║\n║     - Both achieve 85-95% success                          ║\n║     - Non-inferior by RCT evidence                         ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  2. GERD: LHM + Fundoplication < POEM (Level 1)           ║\n║     - 15-25% vs 35-50%                                     ║\n║     - Fundoplication provides protection                   ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  3. TYPE III: POEM > LHM (Level 2-3)                       ║\n║     - Extended myotomy capability                          ║\n║     - 85-95% vs 60-70% success                            ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  4. REDO/SALVAGE: POEM effective (Level 2-3)              ║\n║     - Good option after failed prior treatment             ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  5. LONG-TERM: More data needed for POEM                   ║\n║     - LHM has 20+ years of data                           ║\n║     - POEM only since 2010                                ║\n║                                                             ║\n╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝\n```\n\n### Guideline Recommendations\n\n| Guideline | Recommendation |\n|-----------|----------------|\n| ACG 2020 | PD, LHM, POEM all first-line for Type I/II |\n| SAGES 2022 | Both LHM and POEM acceptable |\n| ESGE 2020 | POEM or LHM based on expertise |\n| ISDE 2018 | POEM preferred for Type III |\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n1. Werner YB, et al. Endoscopic or Surgical Myotomy in Patients with Idiopathic Achalasia. NEJM 2019.\n2. Ponds FA, et al. Effect of Peroral Endoscopic Myotomy vs Pneumatic Dilation on Symptom Severity and Treatment Outcomes. JAMA 2019.\n3. Vaezi MF, et al. ACG Clinical Guidelines: Diagnosis and Management of Achalasia. Am J Gastroenterol 2020.\n4. Khashab MA, et al. POEM: Outcomes and Comparison with LHM. Gastrointest Endosc 2020.\n5. Inoue H, et al. Per-oral Endoscopic Myotomy: 10-year Follow-up. Ann Surg 2019.\n\n---\n\n## Navigation\n\n**Related Notes:**\n- [[03 Spaces/🔬 Active Projects/Learning Modules/Learning System/Study Library/02 - Concept Notes/Esophagus/Achalasia Cardia]] - Pathogenesis and overview\n- [[Esophageal Motility Disorders]] - Classification\n- [[GERD Surgical Management]] - Fundoplication options\n\n**Study Materials:**\n- [[GRINDE Map - Achalasia LHM vs POEM]]\n- [[Retrieval Cards - Achalasia LHM vs POEM]]\n- [[Case - Achalasia Treatment Selection]]\n\n---\n*Last updated: January 2026 | Teaching Roster Topic #20*","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
