VALUES (
  'Achalasia Cardia',
  'surgery-esophagus-achalasia-cardia',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# Achalasia Cardia: Pathogenesis & Management\n\n> **Source**: Shackelford Ch 2 (Motility Diagnosis), Ch 19 (Achalasia)\n> **Topic System**: [[Esophagus Index]]\n> **Phase**: Shoot\n\n---\n\n## Pre-Read Questions (Aim Phase)\n\n1. What is achalasia and what causes it at the cellular level?\n2. How do I diagnose achalasia and differentiate it from pseudoachalasia?\n3. What are the Chicago Classification subtypes and why do they matter?\n4. How do I choose between pneumatic dilation, Heller myotomy, and POEM?\n\n---\n\n## Core Concepts (Shoot Phase)\n\n### Definition & Overview\n\n> [!summary] One-liner\n> Achalasia is a primary esophageal motility disorder characterized by **incomplete LES relaxation** and **absent peristalsis** in the esophageal body, caused by degeneration of inhibitory ganglion cells in the myenteric plexus.\n\n### Key Points\n\n1. **Pathophysiology**: Loss of inhibitory neurons (NO, VIP) → unopposed excitatory input → LES fails to relax\n2. **Cardinal features**: Dysphagia to BOTH solids AND liquids from onset + regurgitation\n3. **Diagnosis**: High-resolution manometry (HRM) is gold standard; barium swallow shows \"bird''s beak\"\n4. **Treatment goal**: Disrupt the LES (not restore peristalsis) - PD, Heller myotomy, or POEM\n5. **Cancer risk**: 0.5-1% annual risk of esophageal squamous cell carcinoma after 15-20 years\n\n### Clinical Relevance\n\n- **When to think about this**: Dysphagia to solids AND liquids equally, regurgitation, chest pain, weight loss\n- **Red flags**: Rapid onset, age >55, significant weight loss → rule out pseudoachalasia (malignancy)\n- **Decision points**: Chicago subtype guides treatment selection; Type II best outcomes, Type III most challenging\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Notes\n\n### Anatomy Review - Lower Esophageal Sphincter\n\n```\n                    ESOPHAGEAL WALL LAYERS\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │  Mucosa (stratified squamous)               │\n    │  Submucosa                                  │\n    │  Muscularis propria                         │\n    │    ├── Inner circular muscle ←── LES        │\n    │    └── Outer longitudinal muscle            │\n    │  Adventitia (no serosa above diaphragm)     │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n    MYENTERIC (AUERBACH''S) PLEXUS\n    - Located between circular and longitudinal muscle\n    - Contains inhibitory neurons (NO, VIP) and excitatory neurons (ACh)\n    - Coordinates peristalsis and LES relaxation\n```\n\n**LES Components**:\n- Intrinsic: Smooth muscle thickening (3-4 cm)\n- Extrinsic: Right crus of diaphragm (contributes ~50% of barrier)\n- Normal resting pressure: 10-30 mmHg\n- Normal relaxation: To gastric baseline with swallow\n\n### Pathophysiology\n\n#### The Core Defect\n\n```\nNORMAL LES RELAXATION:\nSwallow → Vagal efferent → Myenteric plexus →\n    Inhibitory neurons release NO + VIP →\n        Smooth muscle relaxation → LES opens\n\nACHALASIA:\nSwallow → Vagal efferent → Myenteric plexus →\n    ❌ Inhibitory neurons ABSENT/DEGENERATED →\n        Unopposed excitatory (ACh) input →\n            LES fails to relax + no peristalsis\n```\n\n#### Etiology - What Kills the Neurons?\n\n| Hypothesis | Evidence | Status |\n|------------|----------|--------|\n| **Autoimmune** | Lymphocytic infiltration of myenteric plexus; association with HLA-DQ | Leading theory |\n| **Viral trigger** | HSV-1, measles, varicella antibodies elevated | Possible initiator |\n| **Genetic** | Rare familial cases; Allgrove syndrome (AAA) | Minor role |\n| **Chagas disease** | Trypanosoma cruzi destroys neurons | Secondary achalasia (endemic areas) |\n\n**Histopathology**:\n- Loss of ganglion cells in myenteric plexus\n- Lymphocytic infiltration (CD3+ T cells)\n- Fibrosis of myenteric plexus\n- Relative preservation of excitatory neurons\n\n#### Progression of Disease\n\n```\nStage 1: Early\n├── Ganglion cell loss begins\n├── LES hypertensive but can still relax partially\n└── Intermittent dysphagia\n\nStage 2: Established\n├── Significant neuron loss\n├── LES fails to relax\n├── Absent peristalsis\n└── Esophageal dilation begins\n\nStage 3: End-stage\n├── Complete neuron loss\n├── Massively dilated, tortuous esophagus (\"sigmoid esophagus\")\n├── Megaesophagus\n└── Aspiration, malnutrition\n```\n\n### Clinical Presentation\n\n#### Symptoms\n\n| Symptom              | Frequency | Characteristics                          |\n| -------------------- | --------- | ---------------------------------------- |\n| **Dysphagia**        | 95-100%   | Solids AND liquids equally from onset    |\n| **Regurgitation**    | 75-90%    | Undigested food, often nocturnal         |\n| **Chest pain**       | 40-60%    | Retrosternal, can mimic cardiac          |\n| **Weight loss**      | 30-50%    | Progressive; red flag if rapid           |\n| **Heartburn**        | 20-40%    | Paradoxical; from fermentation, not acid |\n| **Aspiration/cough** | 10-30%    | Nocturnal, recurrent pneumonia           |\n\n> [!tip] Clinical Pearl\n> **\"Solids AND liquids from the start\"** = think achalasia\n> **\"Solids first, then liquids later\"** = think mechanical obstruction (stricture, cancer)\n\n#### Maneuvers Patients Use\n- Raising arms overhead\n- Standing/walking after eating\n- Valsalva maneuver\n- Drinking carbonated beverages\n- Arching back\n\n### Diagnosis\n\n#### Diagnostic Algorithm\n\n```\n        Dysphagia to solids + liquids\n                    │\n                    ▼\n        ┌───────────────────┐\n        │  Upper Endoscopy  │ ← Rule out mechanical obstruction\n        └─────────┬─────────┘\n                  │\n        ┌─────────▼─────────┐\n        │ Barium Swallow    │ ← Bird''s beak, dilated esophagus\n        └─────────┬─────────┘\n                  │\n        ┌─────────▼─────────┐\n        │ High-Resolution   │ ← GOLD STANDARD\n        │ Manometry (HRM)   │   Chicago Classification\n        └─────────┬─────────┘\n                  │\n            ┌─────┴─────┐\n            ▼           ▼\n      Type I/II      Type III\n     (Classic)    (Spastic/Vigorous)\n```\n\n#### Investigations\n\n**1. Upper Endoscopy (EGD)**\n- Purpose: Rule out mechanical obstruction, pseudoachalasia (tumor)\n- Findings in achalasia:\n  - Dilated esophagus with retained food/saliva\n  - \"Puckered\" or \"rosette\" LES\n  - Resistance at GEJ but scope passes with gentle pressure\n  - Normal-appearing mucosa\n- **Critical**: Biopsy GEJ to exclude malignancy if suspicious\n\n**2. Barium Swallow**\n\n| Finding | Description |\n|---------|-------------|\n| **Bird''s beak** | Smooth tapering at GEJ (pathognomonic) |\n| **Dilated esophagus** | Loss of peristaltic waves |\n| **Air-fluid level** | Retained barium and secretions |\n| **Sigmoid esophagus** | Tortuous, massively dilated (end-stage) |\n| **Epiphrenic diverticulum** | May be associated |\n\n**3. High-Resolution Manometry (HRM) - Gold Standard**\n\n**Chicago Classification v4.0 Criteria**:\n\n| Parameter | Normal | Achalasia |\n|-----------|--------|-----------|\n| **IRP (Integrated Relaxation Pressure)** | <15 mmHg | **>15 mmHg** |\n| **Peristalsis** | Normal | **Absent (100% failed)** |\n\n**Chicago Classification Subtypes**:\n\n| Type | Esophageal Body | Prevalence | Treatment Response |\n|------|-----------------|------------|-------------------|\n| **Type I** | Absent peristalsis, no pressurization | 20-40% | Good |\n| **Type II** | Panesophageal pressurization (>20% swallows) | 50-70% | **Best** (>90% success) |\n| **Type III** | Spastic contractions (≥20% premature, DCI >450) | 10-15% | **Worst** (variable) |\n\n```\nTYPE I (Classic)              TYPE II (With compression)      TYPE III (Spastic)\n\n  ░░░░░░░░░░░░░               ████████████                    ~~~~≈≈≈≈~~~~\n  ░░░░░░░░░░░░░               ████████████                    ≈≈≈≈~~~~≈≈≈≈\n  ░░░░░░░░░░░░░               ████████████                    ~~~~≈≈≈≈~~~~\n  ▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓               ▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓                    ▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓\n     No activity              Uniform pressure               Spastic waves\n     (aperistalsis)           (panesophageal)               (premature)\n```\n\n**4. Timed Barium Esophagram (TBE)**\n- Barium column height at 1, 2, 5 minutes\n- Objective measure of esophageal emptying\n- Useful for post-treatment follow-up\n\n**5. EndoFLIP (Functional Lumen Imaging Probe)**\n- Measures GEJ distensibility\n- Emerging tool; useful intraoperatively\n- Distensibility index <2.8 mm²/mmHg suggests inadequate myotomy\n\n### Pseudoachalasia (Must Exclude!)\n\n| Feature | True Achalasia | Pseudoachalasia |\n|---------|---------------|-----------------|\n| **Age** | Any (peak 30-60) | Usually >55 |\n| **Duration** | Months to years | Weeks to months |\n| **Weight loss** | Gradual | Rapid, significant |\n| **Barium swallow** | Bird''s beak, smooth | Irregular, shouldered |\n| **EGD** | Passes with gentle pressure | May not pass; mass |\n| **CT scan** | Normal | Thickening, mass, nodes |\n| **Cause** | Primary | Cancer (GEJ adenocarcinoma, lung) |\n\n> [!warning] Red Flags for Pseudoachalasia\n> - Age >55 with new symptoms\n> - Symptom duration <1 year\n> - Rapid weight loss (>7 kg)\n> - Difficulty passing scope at GEJ\n> **→ CT chest/abdomen + EUS before treatment**\n\n### Management\n\n#### Treatment Goals\n1. Relieve symptoms (dysphagia, regurgitation)\n2. Improve esophageal emptying\n3. Prevent complications (aspiration, megaesophagus)\n4. **Note**: Cannot restore peristalsis - treatments disrupt LES only\n\n#### Treatment Options Overview\n\n| Treatment | Mechanism | Durability | Best For |\n|-----------|-----------|------------|----------|\n| **Pneumatic Dilation (PD)** | Controlled tear of LES muscle | 60-85% at 5 yrs (may need repeat) | Type I/II, older patients |\n| **Heller Myotomy (LHM)** | Surgical division of LES muscle | 85-90% at 5-10 yrs | Type I/II, young patients |\n| **POEM** | Endoscopic division of circular muscle | 90-95% at 2-3 yrs | Type I/II/III, failed PD |\n| **Botox injection** | Inhibits ACh release | 50% at 6-12 mo | Elderly, high surgical risk |\n| **Medications** | Smooth muscle relaxation | Minimal | Temporizing only |\n\n#### 1. Pneumatic Dilation (PD)\n\n**Technique**:\n- Rigiflex balloon (30, 35, 40 mm)\n- Fluoroscopic guidance\n- Inflate to obliterate waist at LES\n- Graded approach: Start 30mm → 35mm → 40mm if needed\n\n**Outcomes**:\n- Initial success: 85-90%\n- 5-year success: 60-85% (often requires repeat dilations)\n- Type II responds best\n\n**Complications**:\n| Complication | Incidence | Management |\n|--------------|-----------|------------|\n| **Perforation** | 2-5% | Gastrografin swallow post-procedure; surgery if large |\n| **GERD** | 15-35% | PPI therapy |\n| **Bleeding** | Rare | Usually self-limited |\n\n#### 2. Laparoscopic Heller Myotomy (LHM)\n\n**Technique**:\n```\nHELLER MYOTOMY STEPS:\n1. Position: Supine, split legs, reverse Trendelenburg\n2. Ports: 5 ports, liver retractor\n3. Dissect GEJ, identify anterior vagus\n4. Create window in gastrohepatic ligament\n5. Mobilize distal esophagus (preserve vagus)\n6. MYOTOMY:\n   - Start on esophagus, 6-8 cm proximally\n   - Extend onto gastric cardia 2-3 cm distally\n   - Divide circular muscle fibers\n   - Preserve longitudinal muscle and mucosa\n7. Test for mucosal leak (air insufflation, methylene blue)\n8. FUNDOPLICATION (partial):\n   - Dor (anterior 180°) - preferred, covers myotomy\n   - Toupet (posterior 270°) - alternative\n9. Check hemostasis, remove liver retractor\n```\n\n**Key Technical Points**:\n- Myotomy length: 6-8 cm esophageal + 2-3 cm gastric\n- **Must extend onto stomach** or LES fibers remain\n- Anterior (Dor) fundoplication covers myotomy, prevents reflux\n- Avoid posterior vagus injury\n\n**Outcomes**:\n- Success rate: 85-95%\n- 10-year durability: 80-85%\n- GERD rate: 10-30% (less with fundoplication)\n\n**Complications**:\n| Complication | Incidence | Prevention/Management |\n|--------------|-----------|----------------------|\n| **Mucosal perforation** | 5-10% | Intraop recognition → primary repair + Dor |\n| **Incomplete myotomy** | 5-10% | Extend distally onto stomach |\n| **GERD** | 10-30% | Add partial fundoplication |\n| **Dysphagia recurrence** | 10-15% | May need PD or POEM |\n\n#### 3. POEM (Peroral Endoscopic Myotomy)\n\n**Technique**:\n```\nPOEM PROCEDURE STEPS:\n1. General anesthesia, supine, CO2 insufflation\n2. Mucosal incision: 10-15 cm above GEJ (2 o''clock)\n3. Submucosal tunnel: Inject saline, dissect submucosal plane\n4. Extend tunnel to 2-3 cm onto gastric cardia\n5. MYOTOMY:\n   - Divide circular muscle fibers (±longitudinal for Type III)\n   - Full thickness inner circular myotomy\n   - Spare outer longitudinal muscle\n6. Extend myotomy: 6-10 cm esophageal + 2-3 cm gastric\n7. Close mucosal entry with clips\n8. Gastrografin swallow next day\n```\n\n**Advantages over LHM**:\n- No incisions, less pain\n- Longer myotomy possible (useful for Type III)\n- Posterior myotomy (less prior scarring)\n- Shorter hospital stay\n\n**Disadvantages**:\n- Higher GERD rates (no fundoplication)\n- Requires specific expertise\n- Gas-related complications (pneumomediastinum, pneumoperitoneum)\n\n**Outcomes**:\n- Short-term success: 90-98%\n- 2-3 year success: 90-95%\n- GERD rate: 20-50% (higher than LHM)\n\n**Complications**:\n| Complication | Incidence | Management |\n|--------------|-----------|------------|\n| **Mucosal injury** | 3-5% | Clips, conservative |\n| **Pneumomediastinum** | 10-20% | Usually benign, self-resolves |\n| **Pneumoperitoneum** | 5-10% | Needle decompression if tense |\n| **GERD** | 20-50% | PPI, may need fundoplication later |\n| **Bleeding** | 1-2% | Endoscopic hemostasis |\n\n#### 4. Botulinum Toxin Injection\n\n**Mechanism**: Blocks ACh release at neuromuscular junction → temporary LES relaxation\n\n**Technique**: EGD-guided injection, 100 units divided in 4 quadrants at LES\n\n**Outcomes**:\n- Initial response: 70-80%\n- Duration: 6-12 months (repeat injections needed)\n- Diminishing returns with repeat injections\n\n**Indications**:\n- Elderly patients with high surgical risk\n- Bridge to definitive therapy\n- Patient preference/refusal of surgery\n\n**Downside**: Submucosal fibrosis makes future myotomy more difficult\n\n#### 5. Medications (Limited Role)\n\n| Drug | Class | Dose | Efficacy |\n|------|-------|------|----------|\n| Nifedipine | CCB | 10-20 mg SL before meals | Minimal |\n| Isosorbide dinitrate | Nitrate | 5-10 mg SL before meals | Minimal |\n\n**Use**: Temporizing only; not recommended as definitive therapy\n\n### Treatment Selection Algorithm\n\n```\n                        ACHALASIA DIAGNOSED\n                              │\n                    ┌─────────┴─────────┐\n                    ▼                   ▼\n              Fit for intervention?   Unfit/elderly\n                    │                   │\n                    ▼                   ▼\n              ┌─────┴─────┐         Botox or PD\n              ▼           ▼\n          Type I/II    Type III\n              │           │\n              ▼           ▼\n    ┌─────────┴───────┐   │\n    ▼                 ▼   │\n  Young/            Older │\n  prefer surgery    patient\n    │                 │   │\n    ▼                 ▼   ▼\n  LHM + Dor      PD → POEM (preferred\n  or POEM        (graded)  for Type III)\n```\n\n**Type-Specific Recommendations**:\n| Type | First-line | Alternative | Rationale |\n|------|------------|-------------|-----------|\n| **Type I** | LHM or POEM | PD | Standard response |\n| **Type II** | LHM, POEM, or PD | Any | Best outcomes with all modalities |\n| **Type III** | POEM | Extended LHM | Longer myotomy needed for spastic segment |\n\n### Outcomes Comparison\n\n| Parameter | PD | LHM + Fundoplication | POEM |\n|-----------|-----|---------------------|------|\n| **Initial success** | 85-90% | 90-95% | 95-98% |\n| **5-year success** | 60-85% | 85-90% | 90% (limited data) |\n| **GERD rate** | 15-35% | 10-20% | 20-50% |\n| **Perforation** | 2-5% | 5-10% (controlled) | 3-5% |\n| **Hospital stay** | Outpatient | 1-2 days | 1-2 days |\n| **Repeat procedures** | Often needed | Rarely | Rarely |\n\n### Long-term Surveillance\n\n**Cancer Risk**:\n- Squamous cell carcinoma: 0.5-1% per year after 15-20 years\n- Mechanism: Chronic irritation, stasis, bacterial overgrowth\n- **Surveillance**: EGD every 3-5 years after 10-15 years of disease\n\n**Follow-up**:\n- TBE at 3-6 months post-treatment\n- Symptom assessment\n- EGD if symptoms recur or for cancer surveillance\n\n### Special Situations\n\n#### End-Stage Achalasia (Sigmoid Esophagus)\n- Massively dilated (>6 cm), tortuous\n- May not respond to myotomy/POEM\n- Options:\n  - Trial of POEM/LHM (some respond)\n  - Esophagectomy if failed or megaesophagus\n\n#### Failed Primary Treatment\n- Failed PD → POEM or LHM\n- Failed LHM → POEM (different approach - posterior)\n- Failed POEM → Redo POEM (opposite side) or LHM\n- Multiple failures → Esophagectomy\n\n#### Achalasia + Hiatal Hernia\n- Repair hernia at time of myotomy\n- POEM may be challenging\n\n---\n\n## Connections (Skin Phase)\n\n### Links to Other Concepts\n\n- **Prerequisite knowledge**: [[Esophageal Anatomy]], [[LES Physiology]], [[Swallowing Mechanism]]\n- **Builds upon**: [[Esophageal Manometry]], [[Esophageal Motility Disorders]]\n- **Leads to**: [[Heller Myotomy Technique]], [[POEM Procedure]], [[Fundoplication]]\n- **Contrasts with**: [[GERD]] (LES hypotensive vs hypertensive), [[Esophageal Cancer]] (pseudoachalasia)\n\n### Cross-Book Synthesis\n\n| Aspect | Shackelford Focus                                   |\n| ------ | --------------------------------------------------- |\n| Ch 2   | Manometry technique, Chicago Classification details |\n| Ch 19  | Treatment algorithms, surgical technique, outcomes  |\n|        |                                                     |\n\n---\n\n## Retrieval Practice\n\n### Quick Recall Questions\n\n1. Q: What is the pathophysiologic basis of achalasia?\n   A: Loss of inhibitory ganglion cells (NO, VIP) in myenteric plexus → unopposed excitatory input → failed LES relaxation + absent peristalsis\n\n2. Q: What Chicago Classification type has the best treatment outcomes?\n   A: Type II (panesophageal pressurization) - >90% success with any modality\n\n3. Q: How long should a Heller myotomy extend onto the gastric cardia and why?\n   A: 2-3 cm onto stomach; shorter extension leaves residual LES fibers causing persistent dysphagia\n\n### Self-Assessment\n\nAfter reviewing, rate your understanding (1-5):\n- [ ] 1 - Cannot recall basics\n- [ ] 2 - Recall basics but not applications\n- [ ] 3 - Can apply in familiar contexts\n- [ ] 4 - Can apply in novel situations\n- [ ] 5 - Can teach this to others\n\n---\n\n## Session Log\n\n| Date | Phase | Time Spent | Notes |\n|------|-------|------------|-------|\n| 2025-01-07 | Shoot | 60 min | Complete concept note |\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Shackelford Ch 2: *Esophageal Motility Techniques for Diagnosis*\n- Shackelford Ch 19: *Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment*\n- ISDE Achalasia Guidelines 2018\n- Chicago Classification v4.0 (2021)\n\n---\n\n*VPReFRE Checklist:*\n- [x] **V**isual: Contains diagrams/maps\n- [x] **P**rocessed: In own words, not copied\n- [x] **Re**lational: Connected to other concepts\n- [ ] **F**reehand: Key sketches included\n- [x] **R**eflective: Personal insights added\n- [x] **E**fficient: No redundant information","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
  '> Source: Shackelford Ch 2 (Motility Diagnosis), Ch 19 (Achalasia)
