VALUES (
  'Esophageal Anatomy',
  'surgery-esophagus-esophageal-anatomy',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# Esophageal Anatomy\n\n> **Source**: Shackelford Ch 1 - *Anatomy of the Esophagus and the Gastroesophageal Reflux Barrier*\n> **Topic System**: [[Esophagus Index]]\n> **Phase**: Shoot\n> **Tier**: 1 (Foundation)\n\n---\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n> [!summary] One-liner\n> The esophagus is a 25cm muscular tube extending from C6 to T11, with three anatomical narrowings, transitioning from striated to smooth muscle, and lacking a serosa—making anastomotic leaks more common.\n\n---\n\n## Gross Anatomy\n\n### Length and Position\n\n| Parameter | Value |\n|-----------|-------|\n| **Total length** | 25 cm (range 18-26 cm) |\n| **Cervical** | 5 cm (C6 to thoracic inlet) |\n| **Thoracic** | 17 cm (thoracic inlet to diaphragm) |\n| **Abdominal** | 2-3 cm (diaphragm to GEJ) |\n\n### Distance from Incisors\n\n| Landmark | Distance from Incisors |\n|----------|----------------------|\n| **Cricopharyngeus (UES)** | 15-18 cm |\n| **Aortic arch** | 22-25 cm |\n| **Left main bronchus** | 27-30 cm |\n| **Diaphragmatic hiatus** | 38-40 cm |\n| **GEJ** | 40-42 cm |\n\n### Three Anatomical Narrowings\n\n```\n    ESOPHAGEAL NARROWINGS\n    ═════════════════════\n\n    1. CRICOPHARYNGEAL (UES) ─── 15 cm ─── C6 level\n       Narrowest point (14mm)\n       Common site for Zenker diverticulum\n       Foreign body impaction\n                │\n                │\n    2. AORTIC/BRONCHIAL ─────── 25 cm ─── T4-5 level\n       Aortic arch + left main bronchus\n       External compression\n                │\n                │\n    3. DIAPHRAGMATIC ──────────  40 cm ─── T10-11 level\n       Esophageal hiatus\n       Site of hiatal hernia\n       GEJ location\n```\n\n**Clinical Significance**:\n- **Corrosive injury**: Most severe at narrowings (prolonged contact)\n- **Foreign body impaction**: Most common at cricopharyngeus\n- **Cancer**: 50% occur in middle third (bronchial narrowing)\n\n---\n\n## Wall Layers\n\n### Histological Layers\n\n```\n    ESOPHAGEAL WALL (Inside → Out)\n    ══════════════════════════════\n\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │         MUCOSA                      │\n    │  ┌───────────────────────────────┐  │\n    │  │ Epithelium (stratified        │  │\n    │  │ squamous, non-keratinized)    │  │\n    │  ├───────────────────────────────┤  │\n    │  │ Lamina propria                │  │\n    │  ├───────────────────────────────┤  │\n    │  │ Muscularis mucosae            │  │\n    │  └───────────────────────────────┘  │\n    ├─────────────────────────────────────┤\n    │         SUBMUCOSA                   │\n    │  • Blood vessels, lymphatics        │\n    │  • Submucosal (Meissner''s) plexus   │\n    │  • Esophageal glands                │\n    ├─────────────────────────────────────┤\n    │         MUSCULARIS PROPRIA          │\n    │  ┌───────────────────────────────┐  │\n    │  │ Inner CIRCULAR muscle         │  │ ← LES fibers\n    │  ├───────────────────────────────┤  │\n    │  │ Myenteric (Auerbach''s) plexus │  │ ← Lost in achalasia\n    │  ├───────────────────────────────┤  │\n    │  │ Outer LONGITUDINAL muscle     │  │\n    │  └───────────────────────────────┘  │\n    ├─────────────────────────────────────┤\n    │         ADVENTITIA                  │\n    │  • NO SEROSA (above diaphragm)      │ ← Leak risk\n    │  • Loose connective tissue          │\n    │  • Allows spread of infection       │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n> [!warning] No Serosa = Clinical Implications\n> - Anastomotic leaks more common (no serosal seal)\n> - Cancer spreads earlier to adjacent structures\n> - Perforations spread easily to mediastinum\n> - Sutures don''t hold as well\n\n### Muscle Type Transition\n\n| Level | Muscle Type | Significance |\n|-------|-------------|--------------|\n| **Upper 1/3** | Striated (voluntary) | UES control |\n| **Middle 1/3** | Mixed | Transition zone |\n| **Lower 1/3** | Smooth (involuntary) | LES, affected in achalasia |\n\n---\n\n## Blood Supply\n\n### Arterial Supply (Segmental)\n\n```\n    ESOPHAGEAL ARTERIAL SUPPLY\n    ═══════════════════════════\n\n    CERVICAL\n    └── Inferior thyroid artery (thyrocervical trunk)\n\n    THORACIC\n    ├── Bronchial arteries\n    ├── Aortic esophageal branches (4-6 direct)\n    └── Right intercostal arteries\n\n    ABDOMINAL\n    ├── Left gastric artery (main supply)\n    ├── Left inferior phrenic artery\n    └── Short gastric arteries\n\n    ⚠️ Watershed area: Lower thoracic esophagus\n       (Between aortic and left gastric territories)\n```\n\n### Venous Drainage\n\n| Level | Drainage | Systemic/Portal |\n|-------|----------|-----------------|\n| **Upper** | Inferior thyroid → Brachiocephalic | Systemic |\n| **Middle** | Azygos/Hemiazygos | Systemic |\n| **Lower** | Left gastric (coronary) vein | **Portal** |\n\n> [!tip] Clinical Pearl\n> The lower esophageal veins drain into the **portal system** via left gastric vein. In portal hypertension, these become **esophageal varices** (portosystemic collateral).\n\n---\n\n## Lymphatic Drainage\n\n### Longitudinal Submucosal Plexus\n\n```\n    ESOPHAGEAL LYMPHATICS\n    ═════════════════════\n\n    Key feature: EXTENSIVE LONGITUDINAL SPREAD\n    (Tumor can skip levels → aggressive nodes)\n\n    CERVICAL ────► Deep cervical nodes\n                   Paratracheal nodes\n\n    THORACIC ────► Tracheobronchial nodes\n                   Posterior mediastinal nodes\n                   Subcarinal nodes\n\n    ABDOMINAL ───► Left gastric nodes\n                   Celiac nodes\n                   Para-aortic nodes\n\n    ⚠️ 6cm longitudinal spread in submucosa\n       → Wide margins needed for cancer\n```\n\n**Implications for Cancer Surgery**:\n- 8-10 cm proximal margin recommended for squamous cell carcinoma\n- Skip metastases can occur\n- Two-field or three-field lymphadenectomy may be needed\n\n---\n\n## Nerve Supply\n\n### Extrinsic Innervation\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Function |\n|-------|--------|----------|\n| **Vagus (CN X)** | Brainstem | Parasympathetic - peristalsis, LES relaxation |\n| **Sympathetic** | T1-T10 | Inhibits peristalsis, contracts LES |\n| **Recurrent laryngeal** | Vagus | Motor to upper esophagus (striated) |\n\n### Intrinsic (Enteric) Plexuses\n\n```\n    MYENTERIC (AUERBACH''S) PLEXUS\n    ═════════════════════════════\n    Location: Between circular and longitudinal muscle\n\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                                             │\n    │   EXCITATORY neurons ──► Acetylcholine      │\n    │   (Cause contraction)    Substance P        │\n    │                                             │\n    │   INHIBITORY neurons ──► NO (nitric oxide)  │\n    │   (Cause relaxation)     VIP                │\n    │                                             │\n    │   ⚠️ In ACHALASIA: Inhibitory neurons LOST  │\n    │      → Unopposed excitatory → LES fails     │\n    │        to relax                             │\n    │                                             │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n    SUBMUCOSAL (MEISSNER''S) PLEXUS\n    ═══════════════════════════════\n    Location: Submucosa\n    Function: Regulates secretion, blood flow\n```\n\n---\n\n## Sphincters\n\n### Upper Esophageal Sphincter (UES)\n\n| Component | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Main muscle** | Cricopharyngeus (inferior pharyngeal constrictor) |\n| **Level** | C5-C6 |\n| **Length** | 2-4 cm |\n| **Resting pressure** | 40-100 mmHg |\n| **Muscle type** | Striated (voluntary) |\n| **Relaxation** | Swallow-initiated, vagal mediated |\n\n**Clinical correlates**:\n- Zenker diverticulum (posterior weakness above cricopharyngeus)\n- Cricopharyngeal dysfunction → dysphagia\n\n### Lower Esophageal Sphincter (LES)\n\nSee detailed note: [[LES Physiology]]\n\n| Component | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| **Intrinsic** | Thickened circular smooth muscle (3-4 cm) |\n| **Extrinsic** | Right crus of diaphragm |\n| **Level** | T10-T11, at diaphragmatic hiatus |\n| **Length** | 3-4 cm (1-2 cm intra-abdominal) |\n| **Resting pressure** | 10-30 mmHg (above gastric) |\n| **Muscle type** | Smooth (involuntary) |\n| **Relaxation** | Swallow-initiated, NO/VIP mediated |\n\n---\n\n## Anatomical Relationships\n\n### Thoracic Esophagus Relations\n\n```\n    CROSS-SECTION AT T5 LEVEL\n    ═════════════════════════\n\n              ANTERIOR\n                 │\n         ┌───────┴───────┐\n         │    Trachea    │\n         │    (bifurc)   │\n         └───────────────┘\n                 │\n    LEFT ────────┼──────── RIGHT\n    Aortic arch  │        Azygos vein\n                 │\n         ┌───────────────┐\n         │   ESOPHAGUS   │\n         └───────────────┘\n                 │\n              POSTERIOR\n                 │\n         ┌───────────────┐\n         │  Vertebral    │\n         │  column       │\n         └───────────────┘\n\n\n    LATERAL VIEW\n    ════════════\n\n    Trachea─────┐    ┌─────Aortic arch\n                │    │\n                └──┬─┘\n                   │\n              ┌────┴────┐\n              │Esophagus│───Left main bronchus crosses\n              └────┬────┘   anterior at T5\n                   │\n         ──────────┴────────── Aorta (descends on left,\n                               then posterior)\n```\n\n### Hiatal Anatomy\n\n```\n    ESOPHAGEAL HIATUS (T10)\n    ═══════════════════════\n\n         ┌─────────────────────────────┐\n         │      RIGHT CRUS             │\n         │         ╱   ╲               │\n         │        ╱     ╲              │\n         │       │ Esoph │◄─ Hiatus    │\n         │       │       │             │\n         │        ╲     ╱              │\n         │         ╲   ╱               │\n         │      LEFT CRUS              │\n         └─────────────────────────────┘\n\n    Components of GE Junction:\n    • LES (intrinsic smooth muscle)\n    • Right crus (extrinsic, pinchcock)\n    • Phrenoesophageal ligament\n    • Intra-abdominal esophagus (1-2 cm)\n    • Angle of His (acute cardioesophageal angle)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Clinical Correlations\n\n| Anatomical Feature | Clinical Relevance |\n|-------------------|-------------------|\n| **No serosa** | Higher leak rates, cancer spread |\n| **Three narrowings** | Foreign body, corrosive injury, cancer sites |\n| **Submucosal lymphatics** | Skip metastases, wide margins needed |\n| **Portal venous connection** | Esophageal varices in portal HTN |\n| **Myenteric plexus** | Achalasia (neuron loss), Chagas |\n| **Striated to smooth transition** | Different pathology upper vs lower |\n| **Right crus** | Hiatal hernia when disrupted |\n| **Recurrent laryngeal nerve** | Hoarseness with esophageal surgery/cancer |\n\n---\n\n## Connections\n\n### Links to Other Concepts\n\n- **Leads to**: [[LES Physiology]], [[03 Spaces/🔬 Active Projects/Learning Modules/Learning System/Study Library/02 - Concept Notes/Esophagus/Achalasia Cardia]], [[GERD]]\n- **Related procedures**: [[Esophageal Reconstruction]], [[Heller Myotomy Technique]], [[Fundoplication]]\n- **Related conditions**: [[Zenker Diverticulum]], [[Esophageal Motility Disorders]]\n\n---\n\n## Quick Recall Questions\n\n1. Q: What is the clinical significance of the esophagus lacking a serosa?\n   A: Higher anastomotic leak rates, earlier cancer spread to adjacent structures, easier spread of infection to mediastinum\n\n2. Q: At what distance from the incisors is the GEJ typically located?\n   A: 40-42 cm\n\n3. Q: Which esophageal veins connect to the portal system and cause varices?\n   A: Lower esophageal veins → left gastric (coronary) vein → portal vein\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Shackelford Ch 1: *Anatomy of the Esophagus and the Gastroesophageal Reflux Barrier*\n\n---\n\n*VPReFRE Checklist:*\n- [x] **V**isual: Contains diagrams\n- [x] **P**rocessed: In own words\n- [x] **Re**lational: Connected to other concepts\n- [x] **R**eflective: Clinical correlations added\n- [x] **E**fficient: Focused content","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
