INSERT INTO atoms (title, slug, type, content, summary, specialty, system, topic, subtopic, tags, source_textbook, source_edition, source_chapter, difficulty, read_time_minutes, is_premium, is_published)
VALUES (
  'Esophageal Motility Disorders',
  'surgery-esophagus-esophageal-motility-disorders',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# Esophageal Motility Disorders: Current Classification & Approach to Diagnosis\n\n## Overview\n\nEsophageal motility disorders (EMD) encompass a spectrum of conditions characterized by abnormal esophageal peristalsis and/or lower esophageal sphincter (LES) function. The Chicago Classification v4.0 (2021) provides the current standardized framework for diagnosis based on high-resolution manometry (HRM) findings.\n\n```\nESOPHAGEAL MOTILITY - FUNCTIONAL ANATOMY\n═══════════════════════════════════════\n\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                    PHARYNX                           │\n│                       │                              │\n│              Upper Esophageal                        │\n│              Sphincter (UES)                         │\n│                       │                              │\n│    ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐          │\n│    │     ESOPHAGEAL BODY                  │          │\n│    │                                       │          │\n│    │  Proximal 1/3: Striated muscle       │          │\n│    │  (skeletal - voluntary)              │          │\n│    │           │                          │          │\n│    │  Transition zone                     │          │\n│    │           │                          │          │\n│    │  Distal 2/3: Smooth muscle           │          │\n│    │  (involuntary - peristalsis)         │          │\n│    │                                       │          │\n│    └─────────────────────────────────────┘          │\n│                       │                              │\n│              Lower Esophageal                        │\n│              Sphincter (LES)                         │\n│                       │                              │\n│                   STOMACH                            │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n---\n\n## Normal Esophageal Physiology\n\n### Components of Normal Swallow\n\n```\nNORMAL SWALLOW SEQUENCE\n═══════════════════════\n\nTime (seconds)\n│\n0   ──► UES relaxation + pharyngeal contraction\n│\n│   ──► UES closure\n│\n2   ──► Primary peristaltic wave initiation\n│       (sequential contraction: 3-4 cm/sec)\n│\n│   ──► LES relaxation begins\n│\n6   ──► Peristaltic wave reaches LES\n│\n│   ──► Bolus enters stomach\n│\n8   ──► LES returns to resting tone\n│\n10  ──► Complete\n\nKey Parameters:\n• Peristaltic velocity: 3-4 cm/sec\n• LES resting pressure: 10-35 mmHg\n• Integrated Relaxation Pressure (IRP): <15 mmHg\n• Distal Contractile Integral (DCI): 450-8000 mmHg.cm.s\n```\n\n### Manometric Parameters (Chicago Classification v4.0)\n\n| Parameter | Definition | Normal Value |\n|-----------|------------|--------------|\n| IRP (Integrated Relaxation Pressure) | Mean LES pressure during 4s of relaxation | <15 mmHg |\n| DCI (Distal Contractile Integral) | Amplitude × duration × length of contraction | 450-8000 mmHg.cm.s |\n| DL (Distal Latency) | Time from UES relaxation to CDP | >4.5 seconds |\n| CDP (Contractile Deceleration Point) | Transition from esophageal body to LES segment | - |\n| Break | Gap in 20 mmHg isobaric contour | <3 cm (small) |\n\n---\n\n## Chicago Classification v4.0 (2021)\n\n### Hierarchical Approach\n\n```\nCHICAGO CLASSIFICATION v4.0 - DIAGNOSTIC ALGORITHM\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\n                    ┌──────────────────┐\n                    │  Perform HRM     │\n                    │  (10 swallows)   │\n                    └────────┬─────────┘\n                             │\n                    ┌────────▼─────────┐\n             ┌──────│    IRP ≥15 mmHg  │──────┐\n             │      │      (EGJ OO)     │      │\n            YES     └──────────────────┘     NO\n             │                                 │\n    ┌────────▼────────┐              ┌────────▼────────┐\n    │ EGJ OUTFLOW     │              │   PERISTALTIC   │\n    │ OBSTRUCTION     │              │   DISORDERS     │\n    └────────┬────────┘              └────────┬────────┘\n             │                                 │\n    ┌────────▼────────────────────────────────▼────────┐\n    │                                                   │\n    │  STEP 1: Assess Peristalsis Pattern              │\n    │                                                   │\n    │  • 100% failed = Type I Achalasia               │\n    │  • Panesophageal pressurization = Type II       │\n    │  • Spastic/premature = Type III                 │\n    │  • Some peristalsis = EGJOO                     │\n    │                                                   │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Category 1: Disorders of EGJ Outflow\n\n#### 1.1 Achalasia (IRP ≥15 mmHg + 100% failed peristalsis)\n\n| Subtype | Manometric Features | Clinical Significance |\n|---------|---------------------|----------------------|\n| Type I | No esophageal pressurization, absent peristalsis | \"Classic\" - 32% of cases |\n| Type II | Panesophageal pressurization ≥20% swallows | Best treatment response - 50% |\n| Type III | Premature (spastic) contractions ≥20% swallows | Worst prognosis - 18% |\n\n#### 1.2 EGJ Outflow Obstruction (EGJOO)\n\n- IRP ≥15 mmHg\n- NOT meeting criteria for achalasia\n- Some preserved peristalsis\n- **Requires additional workup** - may be:\n  - Early achalasia\n  - Mechanical obstruction (tumor, stricture)\n  - Medication effect (opioids)\n  - Artifact\n\n```\nEGJOO - DIAGNOSTIC WORKUP\n═════════════════════════\n\n    EGJOO on HRM\n         │\n         ▼\n┌─────────────────────┐\n│  Confirm with       │\n│  Provocative Tests: │\n│  • MRS (Multiple    │\n│    Rapid Swallow)   │\n│  • Solid swallow    │\n│  • RDC (Rapid Drink │\n│    Challenge)       │\n└─────────┬───────────┘\n          │\n    ┌─────▼─────┐\n    │ Confirmed │\n    └─────┬─────┘\n          │\n          ▼\n┌─────────────────────┐\n│  Rule out:          │\n│  • EGD (stricture)  │\n│  • CT/EUS (tumor)   │\n│  • Medication review│\n└─────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Category 2: Major Disorders of Peristalsis\n\n| Disorder | DCI | Other Criteria | IRP |\n|----------|-----|----------------|-----|\n| Absent Contractility | 100% failed (DCI <100) | - | Normal |\n| Distal Esophageal Spasm | ≥20% premature contractions | DL <4.5s | Normal |\n| Hypercontractile (Jackhammer) | ≥20% with DCI >8000 | - | Normal |\n\n#### 2.1 Absent Contractility\n- 100% failed peristalsis\n- Normal IRP (differentiates from Type I achalasia)\n- Associated with:\n  - Scleroderma/Systemic sclerosis\n  - Severe GERD\n  - Post-surgical states\n\n#### 2.2 Distal Esophageal Spasm (DES)\n- ≥20% premature contractions (DL <4.5s)\n- Normal IRP\n- \"Corkscrew esophagus\" on barium swallow\n- Chest pain and dysphagia\n\n#### 2.3 Hypercontractile Esophagus (Jackhammer)\n- ≥20% swallows with DCI >8000 mmHg.cm.s\n- Normal IRP\n- Can affect any segment\n- \"Nutcracker\" is outdated term (referred to amplitude only)\n\n### Category 3: Minor Disorders of Peristalsis\n\n| Disorder | Criteria |\n|----------|----------|\n| Ineffective Esophageal Motility (IEM) | >70% ineffective swallows (failed or weak: DCI <450) |\n| Fragmented Peristalsis | ≥50% fragmented contractions (break >5 cm) |\n\n```\nINEFFECTIVE ESOPHAGEAL MOTILITY - CLINICAL SIGNIFICANCE\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\n        IEM Finding\n             │\n    ┌────────┼────────┐\n    │        │        │\n    ▼        ▼        ▼\n Primary   GERD    Systemic\n  IEM    Related   Disease\n\n• May be         • Impaired      • Scleroderma\n  clinically       bolus          • Diabetes\n  insignificant    clearance      • Hypothyroid\n• Observe        • Contributes   • Post-surgical\n                   to symptoms\n```\n\n---\n\n## Clinical Presentation\n\n### Symptoms by Disorder Type\n\n| Symptom | Achalasia | EGJOO | DES | Hypercontractile | IEM |\n|---------|-----------|-------|-----|------------------|-----|\n| Dysphagia (solids) | +++ | ++ | ++ | ++ | + |\n| Dysphagia (liquids) | +++ | + | ++ | + | - |\n| Regurgitation | +++ | ++ | + | + | - |\n| Chest pain | + | + | +++ | +++ | - |\n| Heartburn | + | + | + | + | ++ |\n| Weight loss | ++ | + | - | - | - |\n\n### Red Flags (\"ALARMS\")\n\n- **A**ge >55 with new symptoms\n- **L**ymph nodes/Mass on imaging\n- **A**nemia (iron deficiency)\n- **R**apid progression\n- **M**elanotic stools/Hematemesis\n- **S**wallowing difficulty progressive\n\n---\n\n## Diagnostic Approach\n\n### Step-by-Step Algorithm\n\n```\nDIAGNOSTIC ALGORITHM FOR DYSPHAGIA\n══════════════════════════════════\n\n                DYSPHAGIA\n                    │\n        ┌───────────┼───────────┐\n        │           │           │\n    Oropharyngeal  Transfer   Esophageal\n    (difficulty    (both)     (food stuck)\n     initiating)                   │\n        │                          │\n        ▼                          ▼\n    Videofluoro-           ┌───────────────┐\n    scopy/ENT              │      EGD      │\n                           │  (First-line) │\n                           └───────┬───────┘\n                                   │\n                    ┌──────────────┼──────────────┐\n                    │              │              │\n                Structural    Eosinophilic    Normal\n                Lesion        Esophagitis        │\n                    │              │              │\n                    ▼              ▼              ▼\n                 Treat          Treat         ┌─────┐\n                                              │ HRM │\n                                              └──┬──┘\n                                                 │\n                                     ┌───────────┴───────────┐\n                                     │                       │\n                                 Abnormal                 Normal\n                                     │                       │\n                             Chicago Class              Functional\n                             Diagnosis                  Dysphagia\n```\n\n### High-Resolution Manometry (HRM)\n\n**Gold Standard for Motility Disorders**\n\n```\nHRM SETUP AND INTERPRETATION\n════════════════════════════\n\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                  HRM CATHETER                    │\n│                                                  │\n│  36 circumferential sensors at 1 cm intervals   │\n│                                                  │\n│      ┌───┐                                      │\n│      │UES│ ← Proximal sensors                   │\n│      └─┬─┘                                      │\n│        │                                        │\n│   ╔════╧════╗                                   │\n│   ║  Body   ║ ← Multiple sensors                │\n│   ║ sensors ║                                   │\n│   ╚════╤════╝                                   │\n│        │                                        │\n│      ┌─┴─┐                                      │\n│      │LES│ ← Distal sensors                     │\n│      └───┘                                      │\n│                                                  │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nColor Plot Interpretation:\n• Purple/Blue = Low pressure (relaxation)\n• Green/Yellow = Moderate pressure\n• Red/White = High pressure (contraction)\n```\n\n**Protocol:**\n1. Fasting 6 hours\n2. Catheter placed transnasally\n3. 10 supine water swallows (5ml each)\n4. Additional tests as needed:\n   - Multiple Rapid Swallow (MRS)\n   - Solid swallow\n   - Rapid Drink Challenge (RDC)\n   - Upright swallows\n\n### Adjunctive Tests\n\n| Test | Role | Key Findings |\n|------|------|--------------|\n| Barium Swallow | Structural assessment | Bird''s beak (achalasia), Corkscrew (DES) |\n| Timed Barium Esophagogram | Quantify emptying | >5cm column at 5 min = delayed |\n| FLIP (EndoFLIP) | EGJ distensibility | Reduced in achalasia (EGJ-DI <2.8 mm²/mmHg) |\n| pH/Impedance | Acid exposure, reflux | Rule out GERD |\n| CT Chest | Mass, dilation | Rule out pseudoachalasia |\n| EUS | Submucosal lesion | Rule out secondary causes |\n\n---\n\n## Specific Disorders - Detailed\n\n### Achalasia Subtypes\n\n```\nACHALASIA SUBTYPES - MANOMETRIC PATTERNS\n════════════════════════════════════════\n\nTYPE I (Classic)                     TYPE II (with compression)\n─────────────────                    ─────────────────────────\n    UES                                   UES\n     │                                     │\n   ──┼────────                           ──┼────────\n     │     │   No                          │  █████│  Pan-esophageal\n   ──┼─────│   pressurization            ──┼──█████│  pressurization\n     │     │                               │  █████│  ≥20% swallows\n   ──┼─────│                             ──┼──█████│\n     │     │                               │       │\n    LES ═══╪═══ (non-relaxing)           LES ═══╪═══ (non-relaxing)\n\n\nTYPE III (Spastic)\n──────────────────\n    UES\n     │\n   ──┼────────\n     │  ██│     Premature\n   ──┼████│     spastic\n     │████│     contractions\n   ──┼██──│     ≥20% swallows\n     │    │     DL <4.5s\n    LES ═══╪═══ (non-relaxing)\n```\n\n### Distinguishing Achalasia from Pseudoachalasia\n\n| Feature | Primary Achalasia | Pseudoachalasia |\n|---------|------------------|-----------------|\n| Age | Any age, peak 30-60 | Usually >55 years |\n| Duration | Gradual (months-years) | Rapid (weeks-months) |\n| Weight loss | Mild-moderate | Severe (>15 lbs) |\n| EGD | Dilated, retained food | May show mass/infiltration |\n| CT/EUS | No mass | Tumor at EGJ |\n| Manometry | Classic pattern | May be atypical |\n\n---\n\n## Treatment Principles by Disorder\n\n```\nTREATMENT ALGORITHM BY DISORDER\n═══════════════════════════════\n\nDISORDER                    FIRST-LINE           ALTERNATIVES\n────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nAchalasia I/II      →   PD or LHM/POEM    →   Botox (high risk)\nAchalasia III       →   POEM              →   LHM + myotomy ext.\nEGJOO               →   Observation/PD    →   Based on etiology\nDES                 →   Medical (CCB/TCA) →   POEM if refractory\nHypercontractile    →   Medical (CCB/TCA) →   POEM if refractory\nIEM                 →   Treat GERD if present\nAbsent contractility →   Prokinetics, GERD tx\n\nPD = Pneumatic Dilation\nLHM = Laparoscopic Heller Myotomy\nPOEM = Per-Oral Endoscopic Myotomy\nCCB = Calcium Channel Blockers\nTCA = Tricyclic Antidepressants\n```\n\n### Medical Management Options\n\n| Drug Class | Examples | Mechanism | Use |\n|------------|----------|-----------|-----|\n| Calcium Channel Blockers | Nifedipine 10-30mg | Smooth muscle relaxation | DES, Hypercontractile |\n| Nitrates | Isosorbide dinitrate 5-10mg | NO-mediated relaxation | DES, Achalasia (bridge) |\n| Tricyclic Antidepressants | Amitriptyline 10-25mg | Pain modulation | DES, Hypercontractile |\n| PDE5 Inhibitors | Sildenafil | Smooth muscle relaxation | DES |\n| Botulinum Toxin | 100 units into LES | Acetylcholine blockade | Poor surgical candidates |\n\n---\n\n## Key Points for Examination\n\n### Must-Know Facts\n\n1. **Chicago Classification v4.0** is the current standard (2021)\n2. **IRP ≥15 mmHg** defines EGJ outflow obstruction\n3. **Achalasia requires**: Elevated IRP + 100% failed peristalsis\n4. **Type II achalasia** has best treatment response\n5. **EGJOO** needs additional workup - not all require treatment\n6. **DES**: Premature contractions (DL <4.5s), NOT high amplitude\n7. **Jackhammer**: DCI >8000, not just high amplitude\n8. **IEM** may be clinically insignificant\n\n### Common Exam Questions\n\n| Question Type | Key Point |\n|---------------|-----------|\n| Differentiate Type I vs II achalasia | Panesophageal pressurization in Type II |\n| Pseudoachalasia workup | CT/EUS to rule out malignancy |\n| When to treat EGJOO | Only if symptomatic + confirmed |\n| DES vs Achalasia III | IRP normal in DES, elevated in Achalasia III |\n| IEM significance | Often secondary to GERD, may not need specific treatment |\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n1. Yadlapati R, et al. Esophageal Motility Disorders on High-Resolution Manometry: Chicago Classification Version 4.0. Neurogastroenterol Motil. 2021.\n2. Kahrilas PJ, et al. The Chicago Classification of Esophageal Motility Disorders, v3.0. Neurogastroenterol Motil. 2015.\n3. Vaezi MF, et al. ACG Clinical Guidelines: Diagnosis and Management of Achalasia. Am J Gastroenterol. 2020.\n4. Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 8th Ed - Chapters 1-12.\n\n---\n\n## Navigation\n\n**Related Notes:**\n- [[03 Spaces/🔬 Active Projects/Learning Modules/Learning System/Study Library/02 - Concept Notes/Esophagus/Achalasia Cardia]] - Detailed achalasia management\n- [[GERD Surgical Management]] - Fundoplication options\n- [[Esophageal Reconstruction]] - Post-resection options\n\n**Study Materials:**\n- [[GRINDE Map - Esophageal Motility Disorders]]\n- [[Retrieval Cards - Esophageal Motility Disorders]]\n- [[Case - Motility Disorder Workup]]\n\n---\n*Last updated: January 2026 | Teaching Roster Topic #18*","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
  'Esophageal motility disorders (EMD) encompass a spectrum of conditions characterized by abnormal esophageal peristalsis and/or lower esophageal sphincter (LES) function. The Chicago Classification v4.0 (2021) provides the current standardized framework for diagnosis based on high-resolution manometr...',
