INSERT INTO atoms (title, slug, type, content, summary, specialty, system, topic, subtopic, tags, source_textbook, source_edition, source_chapter, difficulty, read_time_minutes, is_premium, is_published)
VALUES (
  'Esophageal Reconstruction',
  'surgery-esophagus-esophageal-reconstruction',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# Esophageal Reconstruction: Methods & Outcomes\n\n## Overview\n\nEsophageal reconstruction is required following esophagectomy for malignancy, caustic injury, or end-stage benign disease. The choice of conduit and reconstruction technique significantly impacts outcomes, quality of life, and long-term function. This topic reviews the available options, surgical techniques, and comparative outcomes.\n\n```\nINDICATIONS FOR ESOPHAGEAL RECONSTRUCTION\n═════════════════════════════════════════\n\n┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                                                             │\n│  MALIGNANCY                                                 │\n│  • Esophageal carcinoma (squamous, adenocarcinoma)         │\n│  • GEJ tumors (Siewert I, II)                              │\n│                                                             │\n│  BENIGN CONDITIONS                                          │\n│  • Caustic stricture (failed dilation)                     │\n│  • End-stage achalasia (sigmoid esophagus)                 │\n│  • Refractory peptic stricture                             │\n│  • Esophageal perforation (extensive)                      │\n│                                                             │\n│  CONGENITAL                                                 │\n│  • Long-gap esophageal atresia                             │\n│                                                             │\n└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n---\n\n## Conduit Options\n\n### Comparison Overview\n\n```\nCONDUIT OPTIONS COMPARISON\n══════════════════════════\n\n                    GASTRIC        COLON          JEJUNUM\n                    ───────        ─────          ───────\nPreference          1st choice     2nd choice     3rd choice\n\nBlood Supply        Excellent      Variable       Good\n                    (single axis)  (complex)      (segmental)\n\nReach               Pharynx        Pharynx        Limited\n                    (neck)         (neck)         (mid-chest)\n\nTechnical           Easier         Complex        Complex\nDifficulty\n\nAcid Exposure       Yes            Minimal        None\n\nRedundancy          Rare           Common         Rare\n\nLeak Rate           5-10%          10-15%         5-10%\n\nMortality           3-5%           5-10%          3-5%\n```\n\n### Gastric Conduit (First Choice)\n\n```\nGASTRIC PULL-UP - ANATOMY\n═════════════════════════\n\nBlood Supply Preserved:                 Conduit Creation:\n\n    ┌─────────────────┐                    ┌────────────┐\n    │                 │                    │            │\n    │  Left gastric   │ ← DIVIDE          │   Fundus   │\n    │  (sacrificed)   │                    │  removed   │\n    │                 │                    │            │\n    └────────┬────────┘                    │  ┌────────┤\n             │                             │  │ Staple │\n    ┌────────┴────────┐                    │  │  line  │\n    │   STOMACH       │                    │  │        │\n    │                 │                    │  │  Tube  │\n    │  Right gastric ◄│── PRESERVE        │  │ conduit│\n    │                 │                    │  │        │\n    │  Right gastro-  │                    │  │        │\n    │  epiploic      ◄│── PRESERVE        │  └────────┤\n    │                 │                    │            │\n    └─────────────────┘                    └────────────┘\n\nKey Points:\n• Right gastric and right gastroepiploic arteries preserved\n• Forms vascular arcade along greater curve\n• Left gastric divided (allows mobilization)\n• Short gastrics divided\n• Fundus removed (creates narrow tube)\n• Pyloroplasty/pyloromyotomy for drainage\n```\n\n**Advantages:**\n- Single anastomosis\n- Reliable blood supply\n- Reaches neck easily\n- Technical simplicity\n\n**Disadvantages:**\n- Acid reflux (no sphincter)\n- Loss of reservoir function\n- Dumping syndrome risk\n- Aspiration risk\n\n### Colon Interposition (Second Choice)\n\n```\nCOLON INTERPOSITION - OPTIONS\n═════════════════════════════\n\nLEFT COLON (Most Common):              RIGHT COLON:\n\n    ┌──────────────────┐               ┌──────────────────┐\n    │                  │               │                  │\n    │                  │               │    ┌────────┐   │\n    │    ┌──────┐      │               │    │        │   │\n    │    │      │      │               │    │  Right │   │\n    │    │ Left │      │               │    │ Colon  │   │\n    │    │Colon │      │               │    │        │   │\n    │    │      │      │               │    └────┬───┘   │\n    │    └──┬───┘      │               │         │       │\n    │       │          │               │     Terminal    │\n    │  Left colic      │               │     ileum       │\n    │  vessels         │               │     included    │\n    │  (marginal)      │               │                 │\n    └──────────────────┘               └──────────────────┘\n\nBlood Supply:\n• Left colon: Left colic, marginal artery of Drummond\n• Right colon: Middle colic, ileocolic\n\nRoutes:\n• Retrosternal (most common for benign)\n• Posterior mediastinal (after esophagectomy)\n• Subcutaneous (last resort)\n```\n\n**Indications for Colon:**\n- Previous gastrectomy (no stomach available)\n- Caustic injury involving stomach\n- Failed gastric conduit\n- Long-gap esophageal atresia (pediatric)\n\n**Advantages:**\n- Maintains peristalsis\n- Adequate length\n- No acid production\n- Good for benign disease\n\n**Disadvantages:**\n- Three anastomoses\n- Complex blood supply\n- Redundancy over time\n- Colonic complications (odor, redundancy)\n\n### Jejunal Interposition (Third Choice)\n\n```\nJEJUNAL INTERPOSITION\n═════════════════════\n\nStandard Interposition:               Free Jejunal Transfer:\n\n    ┌────────────────┐                ┌────────────────┐\n    │   Esophagus    │                │   Pharynx      │\n    │       │        │                │       │        │\n    │   ┌───┴───┐    │                │   ┌───┴───┐    │\n    │   │Jejunum│    │                │   │Free   │◄── Microvascular\n    │   │segment│    │                │   │Jejunum│    anastomosis\n    │   └───┬───┘    │                │   └───┬───┘\n    │       │        │                │       │        │\n    │   Stomach/     │                │   Trachea      │\n    │   Jejunum      │                │   stoma        │\n    └────────────────┘                └────────────────┘\n\nBlood Supply:\n• Segmental (jejunal branches of SMA)\n• Mesentery must reach without tension\n• Free flap requires microvascular expertise\n```\n\n**Indications:**\n- Short segment replacement\n- Pharyngeal reconstruction (free flap)\n- After total gastrectomy\n- When colon unavailable\n\n**Advantages:**\n- No acid exposure\n- Active peristalsis\n- No reflux\n\n**Disadvantages:**\n- Limited length (mesenteric constraint)\n- Multiple anastomoses\n- Requires Roux limb\n- Free flap complexity\n\n---\n\n## Surgical Approaches for Esophagectomy\n\n### Route Comparison\n\n```\nESOPHAGECTOMY APPROACHES\n════════════════════════\n\nTRANSTHORACIC (Ivor Lewis/McKeown):\n\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────┐\n    │          Neck incision          │ ← McKeown only\n    │              │                  │   (3-field)\n    │     ┌────────┴────────┐         │\n    │     │   Esophagus     │         │\n    │     │                 │         │\n    │ ════╪════ Diaphragm   │         │\n    │     │                 │         │\n    │     │   Right chest   │ ← Thoracotomy\n    │     │   access        │   (Ivor Lewis)\n    │     │                 │         │\n    │     └────────┬────────┘         │\n    │              │                  │\n    │         Abdomen                 │ ← Laparotomy\n    └─────────────────────────────────┘\n\n\nTRANSHIATAL (Orringer):\n\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────┐\n    │          Neck incision          │\n    │              │                  │\n    │     ┌────────┴────────┐         │\n    │     │   Esophagus     │         │\n    │     │   bluntly       │         │ No thoracotomy!\n    │     │   dissected     │         │\n    │ ════╪════ Diaphragm   │         │\n    │     │                 │         │\n    │     │   Hiatal        │         │\n    │     │   approach      │         │\n    │     │                 │         │\n    │     └────────┬────────┘         │\n    │              │                  │\n    │         Abdomen                 │ ← Laparotomy\n    └─────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Approach Selection\n\n| Approach | Indications | Anastomosis Level |\n|----------|-------------|-------------------|\n| **Ivor Lewis** | Mid/distal esophageal Ca | Intrathoracic (chest) |\n| **McKeown (3-field)** | Upper esophageal Ca | Cervical (neck) |\n| **Transhiatal** | GEJ tumors, benign disease | Cervical (neck) |\n| **Left thoracoabdominal** | GEJ/cardia tumors | Low thoracic |\n| **Minimally invasive (MIE)** | Selected cases | Varies |\n\n---\n\n## Anastomotic Techniques\n\n### Cervical vs Intrathoracic Anastomosis\n\n```\nANASTOMOSIS LOCATION COMPARISON\n═══════════════════════════════\n\nCERVICAL:                          INTRATHORACIC:\n\n     ┌───────┐                          ┌───────┐\n     │ Neck  │ ← Anastomosis            │       │\n     │       │                          │ Chest │ ← Anastomosis\n     └───┬───┘                          │       │\n         │                              └───┬───┘\n     ┌───┴───┐                          ┌───┴───┐\n     │ Chest │                          │       │\n     │       │                          │       │\n     └───┬───┘                          └───┬───┘\n         │                                  │\n     Abdomen                            Abdomen\n\nLeak Rate:      10-15%                  3-5%\nLeak Severity:  Less severe             Life-threatening\n                (drains to neck)        (mediastinitis)\nStricture:      More common             Less common\nRecurrent       Lower risk              Higher risk\nLaryngeal Nerve:\n```\n\n### Anastomotic Techniques\n\n| Technique | Description | Advantages |\n|-----------|-------------|------------|\n| **Hand-sewn** | Single or double layer | Versatile, any location |\n| **Stapled (EEA)** | Circular stapler | Faster, uniform |\n| **Linear stapled** | Side-to-side functional end-to-end | Lower stricture rate |\n| **Semi-mechanical** | Stapled back, hand-sewn front | Combines benefits |\n\n```\nANASTOMOTIC TECHNIQUE OPTIONS\n═════════════════════════════\n\nCIRCULAR STAPLED (EEA):           LINEAR STAPLED (SIDE-TO-SIDE):\n\n    Esophagus                          Esophagus\n        │                                  │\n    ┌───┴───┐                          ┌───┴───┐\n    │  ○○○  │ ← Staple line            │       │\n    │  ○○○  │                          │ ══════│ ← Staple\n    │  ○○○  │                          │       │   closure\n    └───┬───┘                          └───┬───┘\n        │                                  ║\n    Conduit                            ════╬════ ← Side-to-side\n                                           ║      anastomosis\n                                       Conduit\n\nAdvantages:                        Advantages:\n• Quick                            • Larger anastomosis\n• Uniform staple line             • Lower stricture rate\n• Standard technique              • Good blood supply\n```\n\n---\n\n## Postoperative Management\n\n### Early Management\n\n```\nPOST-ESOPHAGECTOMY CARE\n═══════════════════════\n\nDAY 0-3:\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ • ICU monitoring (1-2 days)                              │\n│ • NPO with NG/NJ tube                                    │\n│ • IV fluids, electrolyte monitoring                     │\n│ • Pain management (epidural or PCA)                     │\n│ • Chest tube management (thoracic approach)             │\n│ • DVT prophylaxis                                       │\n│ • Respiratory therapy (incentive spirometry)            │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nDAY 5-7:\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ • Contrast swallow study                                 │\n│ • If no leak → start clear liquids                      │\n│ • Advance diet slowly                                    │\n│ • Chest tubes removed when output low                   │\n│ • Early mobilization                                     │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nDISCHARGE (Day 7-14):\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ • Tolerating soft/pureed diet                           │\n│ • Adequate pain control (oral)                          │\n│ • Feeding tube if needed (J-tube)                       │\n│ • Patient education on eating                           │\n│ • Signs of leak/stricture                               │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Dietary Progression\n\n| Phase | Timing | Foods | Notes |\n|-------|--------|-------|-------|\n| NPO | Days 0-5 | None | IV/enteral via J-tube |\n| Clear liquids | Day 5-7 | Water, broth, juice | After leak test |\n| Full liquids | Week 2 | Protein shakes, soup | Small volumes |\n| Pureed | Week 3-4 | Blended foods | 6-8 small meals |\n| Soft | Week 5-6 | Soft cooked foods | Chew thoroughly |\n| Regular | Week 8+ | Modified regular | Lifelong small meals |\n\n---\n\n## Complications\n\n### Early Complications\n\n```\nEARLY COMPLICATIONS (<30 DAYS)\n══════════════════════════════\n\nANASTOMOTIC LEAK (5-15%)\n────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nTiming: Days 5-10\n\nRisk Factors:              Signs:\n• Poor blood supply        • Fever\n• Tension                  • Tachycardia\n• Technical error         • Leukocytosis\n• Malnutrition            • Neck swelling (cervical)\n• Neoadjuvant therapy     • Pleural effusion (thoracic)\n\nManagement:\n• Cervical: Drain, NPO, antibiotics (usually heals)\n• Thoracic: Emergency! → Re-operation or covered stent\n\n\nCONDUIT NECROSIS (1-3%)\n────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nCause: Vascular compromise\n\nSigns:                     Management:\n• Sepsis                   • Emergency surgery\n• Rapid deterioration     • Takedown anastomosis\n• Dark drainage           • Cervical esophagostomy\n• EGD shows necrosis      • Jejunostomy feeding\n                          • Delayed reconstruction\n\n\nPULMONARY COMPLICATIONS (15-30%)\n────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nTypes:                     Prevention/Treatment:\n• Pneumonia               • Aggressive pulmonary toilet\n• Aspiration              • Early mobilization\n• ARDS                    • Aspiration precautions\n• Respiratory failure     • Antibiotics if infection\n```\n\n### Late Complications\n\n```\nLATE COMPLICATIONS\n══════════════════\n\nANASTOMOTIC STRICTURE (10-30%)\n────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nTiming: 2-6 months post-op\n\nCauses:                    Symptoms:\n• Ischemia                • Progressive dysphagia\n• Leak with healing       • Food impaction\n• Reflux                  • Weight loss\n• Radiation\n\nManagement:\n1. Endoscopic dilation (first-line)\n2. Multiple sessions usually needed\n3. Refractory → stent or revision\n\n\nREFLUX/ASPIRATION\n────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nCause: No LES after reconstruction\n\nPrevention/Management:\n• PPI therapy\n• Elevate head of bed\n• Small frequent meals\n• No eating before bed\n• Consider pyloroplasty\n\n\nDUMPING SYNDROME\n────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nCause: Rapid gastric emptying, vagotomy effect\n\nTypes:\nEarly (15-30 min): Vasomotor symptoms\nLate (1-3 hours): Hypoglycemia\n\nManagement:\n• Small frequent meals\n• Avoid simple sugars\n• Acarbose for late dumping\n```\n\n---\n\n## Outcomes by Conduit\n\n### Comparative Outcomes\n\n```\nOUTCOMES COMPARISON\n═══════════════════\n\n                        GASTRIC     COLON      JEJUNUM\n                        ─────────   ────────   ───────\nOperative mortality     3-5%        5-10%      3-5%\n\nAnastomotic leak        5-10%       10-15%     5-10%\n\nConduit necrosis        1-3%        3-5%       2-4%\n\nStricture rate          10-20%      15-25%     10-15%\n\nHospital stay           10-14 days  14-21 days 12-16 days\n\nFunctional outcome      Good        Good       Good\n\nLong-term survival*     Similar across conduits\n                        (depends on disease stage)\n\n*For malignancy - conduit choice doesn''t affect cancer survival\n```\n\n### Quality of Life\n\n| Aspect | Gastric | Colon | Jejunum |\n|--------|---------|-------|---------|\n| Eating capacity | Fair | Good | Good |\n| Reflux | Common | Rare | Rare |\n| Dumping | Common | Rare | Rare |\n| Redundancy | Rare | Common | Rare |\n| Long-term function | Good | Good | Good |\n\n---\n\n## Special Situations\n\n### Caustic Injury Reconstruction\n\n```\nCAUSTIC INJURY - RECONSTRUCTION PRINCIPLES\n══════════════════════════════════════════\n\nTiming:\n• Acute: Supportive care, assess extent\n• Subacute (2-6 weeks): Avoid surgery (friable tissue)\n• Chronic (>6 months): Reconstruction if indicated\n\nAssessment:\n• EGD (initial and follow-up)\n• Contrast study\n• CT for extent\n• Gastric involvement?\n\nConduit Selection:\n┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                                                         │\n│  Stomach spared → GASTRIC PULL-UP (preferred)          │\n│                                                         │\n│  Stomach involved → COLON INTERPOSITION                │\n│                    (most common for caustic)           │\n│                                                         │\n│  Route: RETROSTERNAL (bypass damaged mediastinum)      │\n│                                                         │\n└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Supercharged Gastric Conduit\n\n```\nSUPERCHARGED CONDUIT\n════════════════════\n\nIndication: Concerns about gastric tip perfusion\n\nTechnique:\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                                          │\n    │  Left internal mammary or              │\n    │  internal jugular vein                  │\n    │           │                              │\n    │     ┌─────┴─────┐                       │\n    │     │Anastomosis│ ← Microvascular      │\n    │     └─────┬─────┘   anastomosis        │\n    │           │                              │\n    │  ┌────────┴────────┐                    │\n    │  │   Gastric tip   │                    │\n    │  │   (enhanced)    │                    │\n    │  └─────────────────┘                    │\n    │                                          │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nPurpose:\n• Augments blood supply to conduit tip\n• Reduces anastomotic complications\n• Consider for long conduit pulls\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Points for Examination\n\n### Must-Know Facts\n\n```\n╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗\n║                    HIGH-YIELD EXAM FACTS                    ║\n╠════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╣\n║                                                             ║\n║  1. GASTRIC CONDUIT = First choice                         ║\n║     • Single anastomosis                                   ║\n║     • Reliable blood supply (right gastric, GE)           ║\n║     • Reaches neck                                         ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  2. COLON INTERPOSITION when:                              ║\n║     • Stomach unavailable (prior gastrectomy)             ║\n║     • Caustic injury involving stomach                     ║\n║     • Failed gastric conduit                               ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  3. BLOOD SUPPLY:                                          ║\n║     • Gastric: Right gastric + Right gastroepiploic       ║\n║     • Colon: Based on marginal artery                     ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  4. CERVICAL vs INTRATHORACIC anastomosis:                ║\n║     • Cervical: Higher leak rate, less severe             ║\n║     • Intrathoracic: Lower leak, but devastating if occurs║\n║                                                             ║\n║  5. PYLOROPLASTY often performed with gastric conduit     ║\n║     (vagotomy effect → delayed emptying)                  ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  6. ANASTOMOTIC LEAK: Most critical complication          ║\n║     • Timing: Days 5-10                                    ║\n║     • Cervical: Usually conservative management           ║\n║     • Intrathoracic: Often needs intervention             ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  7. STRICTURE: Common late complication (10-30%)          ║\n║     • Treat with endoscopic dilation                      ║\n║                                                             ║\n╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝\n```\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n1. Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 8th Ed - Chapters 38-42.\n2. Low DE, et al. International Consensus on Standardization of Esophagectomy. Ann Surg 2019.\n3. Biere SS, et al. Minimally Invasive vs Open Esophagectomy (TIME Trial). Lancet 2012.\n4. Mariette C, et al. Hybrid Minimally Invasive Esophagectomy (MIRO Trial). NEJM 2019.\n\n---\n\n## Navigation\n\n**Related Notes:**\n- [[Surgical Management of GERD]] - Anti-reflux surgery\n- [[Esophageal Motility Disorders]] - Motility assessment\n\n**Study Materials:**\n- [[GRINDE Map - Esophageal Reconstruction]]\n- [[Retrieval Cards - Esophageal Reconstruction]]\n- [[Case - Esophageal Reconstruction Planning]]\n\n---\n*Last updated: January 2026 | Teaching Roster Topic #22*","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
