INSERT INTO atoms (title, slug, type, content, summary, specialty, system, topic, subtopic, tags, source_textbook, source_edition, source_chapter, difficulty, read_time_minutes, is_premium, is_published)
VALUES (
  'Fundoplication',
  'surgery-esophagus-fundoplication',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# Fundoplication\n\n> **Source**: Shackelford Ch 8-10 - *GERD and Antireflux Surgery*, Ch 19 - *Achalasia*\n> **Topic System**: [[Esophagus Index]]\n> **Phase**: Shoot\n> **Tier**: 4 (Surgical Technique)\n\n---\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n> [!summary] One-liner\n> Fundoplication wraps the gastric fundus around the distal esophagus to augment the LES—Nissen (360°) is most effective but requires normal motility; Toupet (270° posterior) or Dor (180° anterior) are partial wraps used with dysmotility or after Heller myotomy.\n\n---\n\n## Indications\n\n### Primary Indications (GERD)\n\n| Indication | Details |\n|------------|---------|\n| **Failed medical therapy** | Persistent symptoms despite optimal PPI |\n| **Patient preference** | Desire to avoid lifelong medication |\n| **Complications of GERD** | Stricture, Barrett''s (controversial), aspiration |\n| **Large hiatal hernia** | Symptomatic Type II, III, IV |\n| **Medication intolerance** | Side effects from PPI |\n| **Volume regurgitation** | Not controlled by acid suppression |\n\n### After Myotomy (Achalasia)\n\n| Setting | Fundoplication Type |\n|---------|---------------------|\n| **Heller myotomy** | Dor (anterior) or Toupet (posterior) |\n| **POEM** | Generally NOT done (no access) |\n| **Failed POEM with GERD** | May need late fundoplication |\n\n---\n\n## Types of Fundoplication\n\n### Comparison Table\n\n| Feature | Nissen (360°) | Toupet (270°) | Dor (180°) |\n|---------|---------------|---------------|------------|\n| **Wrap degree** | Complete | Partial posterior | Partial anterior |\n| **Efficacy** | Highest | Good | Moderate |\n| **Dysphagia risk** | Higher | Lower | Lowest |\n| **For normal motility** | Yes | Yes | Yes |\n| **For poor motility** | No | **Preferred** | Alternative |\n| **After Heller** | No | **Option** | **Preferred** |\n| **Gas-bloat risk** | Higher | Lower | Lowest |\n\n### Visual Comparison\n\n```\n    FUNDOPLICATION TYPES (Cross-section view)\n    ══════════════════════════════════════════\n\n    NISSEN (360°)           TOUPET (270°)           DOR (180°)\n    ═════════════           ═════════════           ═════════\n\n        ┌───┐                   ┌───┐                 ┌───┐\n      ╱─────╲                   │   │               ╱─────╲\n     │░░███░░│               ███│   │███           │ ███  │\n     │░░███░░│               ███│   │███           │ ███  │\n      ╲─────╱                ███│   │███           │      │\n        └───┘                   └───┘                └───┘\n\n    Complete wrap          Posterior only         Anterior only\n    around esophagus       (back 270°)            (front 180°)\n\n    ░░░ = Fundus wrap\n    ███ = Fundus position\n```\n\n---\n\n## Nissen Fundoplication (360°)\n\n### Technique Overview\n\n```\n    NISSEN FUNDOPLICATION - COMPLETE 360° WRAP\n    ═══════════════════════════════════════════\n\n    BEFORE                          AFTER\n    ──────                          ─────\n\n         Esophagus                      Esophagus\n            │                              │\n            │                         ╭────┴────╮\n            │                        ╱░░░░░░░░░░░╲\n            │                       │░░░░░███░░░░░│\n       ─────┴─────                  │░░░░░███░░░░░│\n      /           \\                 │░░░░░███░░░░░│\n     │   Stomach   │                 ╲░░░░░░░░░░░╱\n     │             │                  ╰────┬────╯\n                                           │\n                                       Stomach\n\n    ███ = Esophagus lumen\n    ░░░ = Fundus wrapped around (360°)\n```\n\n### Step-by-Step Technique\n\n#### Port Placement\n\n```\n    LAPAROSCOPIC PORT PLACEMENT\n    ═══════════════════════════\n\n              Camera (10mm)\n                  ●\n                  │\n         ●───────┼───────●\n      Surgeon    │     Surgeon\n       Right     │      Left\n       (5mm)     │     (5mm)\n                 │\n         ●───────┼───────●\n      Liver     │     Assistant\n      retractor │      (5mm)\n       (5mm)    │\n```\n\n#### Key Steps\n\n| Step | Action | Key Points |\n|------|--------|------------|\n| **1** | Liver retraction | Nathanson retractor or flexible retractor |\n| **2** | Divide gastrohepatic ligament | Preserve hepatic branch of vagus if present |\n| **3** | Identify right crus | Start crural dissection |\n| **4** | Mobilize esophagus | Create window behind esophagus |\n| **5** | Identify left crus | Complete posterior dissection |\n| **6** | Divide short gastrics | Mobilize fundus for tension-free wrap |\n| **7** | Crural closure | Posterior closure with permanent suture |\n| **8** | Create wrap | \"Floppy\" Nissen - 2-3 cm, loose |\n| **9** | Secure wrap | 2-3 sutures incorporating esophageal wall |\n\n### The \"Floppy\" Nissen Principles\n\n> [!warning] Critical Technical Points\n> 1. **Short wrap**: 2-2.5 cm (NOT 4-5 cm)\n> 2. **Tension-free**: Divide short gastrics\n> 3. **Fundus-to-fundus**: Use FUNDUS, not body of stomach\n> 4. **Loose**: 52-60 Fr bougie should pass easily\n> 5. **Over esophagus**: Not stomach (avoid slipped Nissen)\n\n```\n    \"SHOE-SHINE\" TEST\n    ═════════════════\n\n    The fundus should easily slide\n    back and forth behind esophagus\n    like a shoe-shine motion\n\n        ←─── Fundus ───→\n             ╱    ╲\n            │ Esoph │\n             ╲    ╱\n    If tight → improper mobilization\n```\n\n---\n\n## Toupet Fundoplication (270° Posterior)\n\n### Indications\n\n- **Impaired esophageal motility** (contraction amplitude <30 mmHg)\n- **After Heller myotomy** (alternative to Dor)\n- **Redo fundoplication** (after failed Nissen)\n- **Patient preference** (lower dysphagia)\n\n### Technique\n\n```\n    TOUPET (270° POSTERIOR)\n    ═══════════════════════\n\n    Cross-sectional view:\n\n         Anterior\n            │\n            ▼\n        ┌───────┐\n        │░░░░░░░│\n        │░░███░░│ ← Esophagus\n        │░░███░░│\n        │       │\n        └───────┘\n            │\n            ▼\n       Posterior\n\n    View from front:\n\n              Esophagus\n                 │\n            ┌────┴────┐\n           ╱    │      ╲\n    Left  │     │       │ Right\n    wrap  │     │       │ wrap\n          │     │       │\n           ╲    │      ╱\n            └───┴────┘\n              │\n          Stomach\n\n    • Each limb sutured to crura AND esophagus\n    • Anterior esophagus remains exposed\n    • 270° coverage posteriorly\n```\n\n---\n\n## Dor Fundoplication (180° Anterior)\n\n### Primary Indication\n\n**After Heller myotomy** - covers and protects the myotomy site\n\n### Advantages After Heller\n\n| Advantage | Explanation |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| **Protects myotomy** | Covers exposed mucosa |\n| **Buttresses repair** | If mucosal injury occurred |\n| **Easier technically** | No posterior dissection needed |\n| **Maintains myotomy** | Less likely to \"close\" the myotomy |\n\n### Technique\n\n```\n    DOR FUNDOPLICATION (180° ANTERIOR)\n    ═══════════════════════════════════\n\n    After Heller Myotomy - Anterior View:\n\n    BEFORE DOR                    AFTER DOR\n    ──────────                    ─────────\n\n         │                            │\n      ┌──┴──┐ ← Myotomy          ┌───┴───┐\n      │░░░░░│   site             │███████│ ← Fundus\n      │░░░░░│   (exposed         │███████│   covers\n      │░░░░░│    mucosa)         │███████│   myotomy\n      ├─────┤                    ├───────┤\n      │     │                    │       │\n    Stomach                    Stomach\n```\n\n---\n\n## Technical Pearls\n\n### Crural Closure\n\n```\n    POSTERIOR CRURAL CLOSURE\n    ════════════════════════\n\n    View from above:\n\n    BEFORE                      AFTER\n    ──────                      ─────\n\n     Left        Right         Left        Right\n     crus        crus          crus        crus\n        ╲        ╱                ╲──●──╱\n         ╲      ╱                  ╲  ╱\n          ╲    ╱        →          ╲╱\n           ╲  ╱                    ││\n            ╲╱                     ││\n            ││                     ││\n         Esophagus              Esophagus\n\n    • Permanent suture (0-Ethibond or silk)\n    • Avoid overtightening (dysphagia)\n    • Should admit fingertip alongside esophagus\n    • Mesh reinforcement if >5cm defect (controversial)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Complications\n\n### Early Complications\n\n| Complication | Incidence | Management |\n|--------------|-----------|------------|\n| **Dysphagia** | 10-50% early | Usually resolves; dilation if persists |\n| **Wrap disruption** | <1% | Reoperation |\n| **Vagal injury** | 1-2% | Supportive; gastroparesis if bilateral |\n| **Splenic injury** | <1% | Splenectomy if uncontrolled |\n| **Esophageal perforation** | <1% | Repair, drain |\n\n### Late Complications\n\n| Complication | Incidence | Management |\n|--------------|-----------|------------|\n| **Recurrent GERD** | 5-10% | PPI, consider redo |\n| **Persistent dysphagia** | 3-5% | Dilation, redo with partial wrap |\n| **Gas-bloat syndrome** | 5-10% | Dietary modification, may improve |\n| **Slipped Nissen** | 2-5% | Redo fundoplication |\n| **Para-esophageal hernia** | 1-2% | Reoperation |\n\n### Slipped Nissen\n\n```\n    SLIPPED NISSEN\n    ══════════════\n\n    NORMAL                      SLIPPED\n    ──────                      ───────\n\n    Wrap around                 Wrap slipped down\n    esophagus                   around stomach\n\n        ┌───┐                      ┌───┐\n       ╱░░░░░╲                     │   │\n      │░░███░░│                    │ E │\n      │░░███░░│                    │   │\n       ╲░░░░░╱                 ───►├───┤\n        └───┘                     ╱░░░░░╲\n          │                      │░░███░░│ ← Wrap now\n          │                       ╲░░░░░╱    around\n       Stomach                      │        stomach\n                                 Stomach\n\n    E = Esophagus\n    ███ = What''s inside the wrap\n\n    Causes: Wrap not secured to esophagus,\n            short esophagus, wrap too loose\n```\n\n---\n\n## Outcomes\n\n### Success Rates\n\n| Outcome | Nissen | Toupet | Dor |\n|---------|--------|--------|-----|\n| **Symptom control** | 85-95% | 80-90% | 75-85% |\n| **Objective reflux control** | 90% | 85% | 80% |\n| **10-year satisfaction** | 80-90% | 80-85% | 75-80% |\n\n---\n\n## Fundoplication After Myotomy\n\n### Why Partial Wrap?\n\n| Reason | Explanation |\n|--------|-------------|\n| **Already compromised LES** | Myotomy disrupts sphincter |\n| **Risk of dysphagia** | Complete wrap + disrupted peristalsis = obstruction |\n| **Match to motility** | Achalasia = aperistalsis |\n\n### Dor vs Toupet After Heller\n\n| Feature | Dor (Anterior) | Toupet (Posterior) |\n|---------|----------------|-------------------|\n| **Myotomy protection** | Yes | No |\n| **Anti-reflux** | Moderate | Better |\n| **Technical ease** | Easier | Requires posterior dissection |\n| **Preference** | Many surgeons prefer | Equal outcomes in studies |\n\n> [!tip] Clinical Pearl\n> **Most surgeons prefer Dor after Heller** because:\n> 1. Covers and protects the myotomy\n> 2. Buttresses any mucosal injury\n> 3. No need for posterior dissection (already done for myotomy)\n> 4. Adequate reflux control in most patients\n\n---\n\n## Connections\n\n### Links to Other Concepts\n\n- **Prerequisite**: [[LES Physiology]], [[Esophageal Anatomy]], [[Esophageal Manometry]]\n- **Primary indication**: [[GERD]], [[Surgical Management of GERD]]\n- **After procedure**: [[Heller Myotomy Technique]], [[POEM Procedure]] (late)\n- **Related**: [[03 Spaces/🔬 Active Projects/Learning Modules/Learning System/Study Library/02 - Concept Notes/Esophagus/Achalasia Cardia]]\n\n---\n\n## Quick Recall Questions\n\n1. Q: What is the key difference between Dor and Toupet fundoplication?\n   A: Dor is 180° anterior (covers front of esophagus), Toupet is 270° posterior (wraps around back)\n\n2. Q: Why is a partial fundoplication preferred after Heller myotomy?\n   A: The LES is already disrupted by myotomy, and complete wrap + aperistalsis = high dysphagia risk\n\n3. Q: What are the 5 principles of a \"floppy\" Nissen?\n   A: Short (2-2.5 cm), tension-free (divide short gastrics), fundus-to-fundus (not body), loose (52-60 Fr bougie), over esophagus (not stomach)\n\n4. Q: What is gas-bloat syndrome?\n   A: Inability to belch/vomit after fundoplication due to effective one-way valve; presents with bloating, early satiety\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Shackelford Ch 8-10: *GERD and Antireflux Surgery*\n- Shackelford Ch 19: *Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment*\n\n---\n\n*VPReFRE Checklist:*\n- [x] **V**isual: Wrap diagrams, suture placement\n- [x] **P**rocessed: Step-by-step technique\n- [x] **Re**lational: Connected to GERD, achalasia, myotomy\n- [x] **R**eflective: Complications and outcomes\n- [x] **E**fficient: Focused content","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
  '> Source: Shackelford Ch 8-10 - *GERD and Antireflux Surgery*, Ch 19 - *Achalasia*
