INSERT INTO atoms (title, slug, type, content, summary, specialty, system, topic, subtopic, tags, source_textbook, source_edition, source_chapter, difficulty, read_time_minutes, is_premium, is_published)
VALUES (
  'GERD - Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease',
  'surgery-esophagus-gerd-gastroesophageal-reflux-disease',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# GERD - Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease\n\n> **Source**: Shackelford Ch 7 - *Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux*, Ch 8 - *GERD*, Ch 9 - *Barrett''s Esophagus*, Ch 10 - *Antireflux Procedures*\n> **Topic System**: [[Esophagus Index]]\n> **Phase**: Shoot\n\n---\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n> [!summary] One-liner\n> GERD results from excessive esophageal acid exposure (>4% time pH <4) primarily due to transient LES relaxations (TLESRs), with diagnosis confirmed by symptoms + endoscopy/pH monitoring, and managed by PPIs first-line with fundoplication for refractory cases or patient preference.\n\n---\n\n## Pathophysiology\n\n### Anti-Reflux Barrier Components\n\n```\n    THE ANTI-REFLUX BARRIER\n    ═══════════════════════\n\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                                                 │\n    │   1. INTRINSIC LES                              │\n    │      • Tonically contracted smooth muscle       │\n    │      • Resting pressure 10-30 mmHg              │\n    │      • 3-4 cm length                            │\n    │                                                 │\n    │   2. CRURAL DIAPHRAGM (Extrinsic)               │\n    │      • Right crus forms sling                   │\n    │      • Augments LES during inspiration          │\n    │      • Contributes ~50% of barrier              │\n    │                                                 │\n    │   3. INTRA-ABDOMINAL ESOPHAGUS                  │\n    │      • 1-2 cm below diaphragm                   │\n    │      • Positive pressure environment            │\n    │                                                 │\n    │   4. ANGLE OF HIS                               │\n    │      • Acute cardioesophageal angle             │\n    │      • Creates mucosal flap valve               │\n    │                                                 │\n    │   5. PHRENOESOPHAGEAL LIGAMENT                  │\n    │      • Anchors GEJ to diaphragm                 │\n    │                                                 │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Mechanisms of Reflux\n\n```\n    THREE MECHANISMS OF REFLUX\n    ══════════════════════════\n\n    1. TRANSIENT LES RELAXATIONS (TLESRs) ──── 50-70% of episodes\n       │\n       ├── NOT triggered by swallowing\n       ├── Triggered by gastric distension\n       ├── Vagal reflex (for venting/belch)\n       └── Duration: 10-60 seconds\n\n    2. HYPOTENSIVE LES ──────────────────────── 20-30% of patients\n       │\n       ├── Resting LES pressure <10 mmHg\n       ├── Free reflux can occur\n       └── Often with hiatal hernia\n\n    3. ANATOMICAL DISRUPTION ────────────────── 40-60% with hiatal hernia\n       │\n       ├── Hiatal hernia separates LES from crura\n       ├── Loss of dual sphincter effect\n       └── \"Acid pocket\" in hernia sac\n```\n\n### The \"Acid Pocket\" Phenomenon\n\n```\n    ACID POCKET IN HIATAL HERNIA\n    ════════════════════════════\n\n    NORMAL                      WITH HIATAL HERNIA\n    ──────                      ──────────────────\n\n    Esophagus                   Esophagus\n        │                           │\n        │                           │\n    ────┼──── Diaphragm        ────┼──── Diaphragm\n        │                       ╭───┴───╮\n        │                       │░░░░░░░│ ← \"Acid pocket\"\n    ────┴────                   │░░░░░░░│   unbuffered acid\n    ╱        ╲                  ╰───┬───╯   in hernia sac\n   │ Stomach  │                     │\n                                ────┴────\n                               ╱         ╲\n                              │  Stomach  │\n\n    ░░░ = Unbuffered gastric acid\n          (escapes meal buffering)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Clinical Presentation\n\n### Typical Symptoms\n\n| Symptom | Description |\n|---------|-------------|\n| **Heartburn** | Retrosternal burning, postprandial, worse supine |\n| **Regurgitation** | Effortless return of gastric contents |\n| **Dysphagia** | May indicate stricture, severe esophagitis, or cancer |\n| **Chest pain** | Can mimic angina; must rule out cardiac first |\n\n### Atypical/Extraesophageal Symptoms\n\n| Symptom | Mechanism |\n|---------|-----------|\n| **Chronic cough** | Microaspiration, vagal reflex |\n| **Hoarseness** | Laryngeal inflammation |\n| **Asthma exacerbation** | Bronchospasm from reflux |\n| **Dental erosions** | Acid effect on enamel |\n| **Globus sensation** | \"Lump in throat\" |\n| **Throat clearing** | Posterior laryngeal irritation |\n\n### Alarm Features (Require EGD)\n\n| Red Flag | Concern |\n|----------|---------|\n| **Dysphagia** | Stricture, malignancy |\n| **Odynophagia** | Ulceration, severe esophagitis |\n| **Weight loss** | Malignancy |\n| **Anemia/GI bleeding** | Ulcer, cancer |\n| **Age >50 with new symptoms** | Barrett''s, malignancy |\n\n---\n\n## Diagnosis\n\n### Diagnostic Algorithm\n\n```\n    GERD DIAGNOSTIC APPROACH\n    ════════════════════════\n\n    Typical symptoms (heartburn, regurgitation)\n                │\n                ▼\n    ┌───────────────────────┐\n    │  Alarm features?      │\n    └───────────┬───────────┘\n           Yes  │  No\n                │   │\n         ┌──────┘   └──────┐\n         ▼                 ▼\n       EGD           PPI Trial (8 weeks)\n         │                 │\n         │           Response?\n         │            │    │\n         │        Yes │    │ No/Partial\n         │            │    │\n         │            ▼    ▼\n         │         GERD   Further testing\n         │       confirmed  │\n         │                  │\n         └──────────────────┤\n                            ▼\n              ┌─────────────────────────┐\n              │  • EGD if not done      │\n              │  • 24-hour pH monitoring│\n              │  • Consider HRM         │\n              └─────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Upper Endoscopy (EGD)\n\n#### LA Classification of Esophagitis\n\n```\n    LA CLASSIFICATION OF REFLUX ESOPHAGITIS\n    ═══════════════════════════════════════\n\n    GRADE A                    GRADE B\n    ─────────                  ─────────\n    ┌─────────────┐            ┌─────────────┐\n    │             │            │             │\n    │    ─        │            │   ───       │\n    │             │            │             │\n    │             │            │   ───       │\n    │             │            │             │\n    └─────────────┘            └─────────────┘\n    Mucosal break             Mucosal break\n    ≤5mm, single fold         >5mm, single fold\n\n    GRADE C                    GRADE D\n    ─────────                  ─────────\n    ┌─────────────┐            ┌─────────────────┐\n    │             │            │ ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░ │\n    │   ───────   │            │ ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░ │\n    │      │      │            │ ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░ │\n    │   ───────   │            │ ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░ │\n    │             │            │ ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░ │\n    └─────────────┘            └─────────────────┘\n    Continuous between        ≥75% circumference\n    ≥2 folds, <75% circumf.\n\n    Grades C and D = SEVERE esophagitis\n    (confirm GERD, correlate with symptoms)\n```\n\n### 24-Hour pH Monitoring\n\n| Technique | Use |\n|-----------|-----|\n| **Catheter-based** | Off PPI x 7 days; measures acid exposure |\n| **Wireless (Bravo)** | Capsule attached to esophagus; more comfortable |\n| **Impedance-pH** | Detects non-acid reflux; use ON PPI |\n\n#### Key Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Normal | Abnormal |\n|-----------|--------|----------|\n| **Total acid exposure time** | <4% | **>6%** |\n| **DeMeester score** | <14.7 | **>14.7** |\n| **Number of reflux episodes** | <50/day | >50/day |\n| **Symptom correlation (SI)** | - | >50% = positive |\n| **SAP** | - | >95% = positive |\n\n```\n    pH MONITORING INTERPRETATION\n    ════════════════════════════\n\n    24-hour pH tracing:\n\n    pH 8 ─┬──────────────────────────────────\n          │\n    pH 4 ─┼─────┬─────┬─────┬─────┬─────────  ← pH 4 threshold\n          │     │     │     │     │\n    pH 2 ─┤     └─────┘     └─────┘\n          │     ▲     ▲\n          │  Reflux episodes\n          └────────────────────────────────→\n              0    6    12   18   24 hours\n\n    Total time pH <4 / Total time = % acid exposure\n```\n\n---\n\n## Complications of GERD\n\n### Esophageal Complications\n\n| Complication | Description | Management |\n|--------------|-------------|------------|\n| **Erosive esophagitis** | LA Grade A-D | PPI, healing in 8-12 weeks |\n| **Stricture** | Fibrotic narrowing | Dilation + PPI |\n| **Barrett''s esophagus** | Intestinal metaplasia | Surveillance, ablation if dysplasia |\n| **Ulceration** | Deep mucosal injury | High-dose PPI |\n| **Adenocarcinoma** | Complicates Barrett''s | Staging, treatment |\n\n### Barrett''s Esophagus\n\n```\n    BARRETT''S ESOPHAGUS\n    ═══════════════════\n\n    Definition: Replacement of normal squamous epithelium\n                with intestinal metaplasia (goblet cells)\n\n    NORMAL                      BARRETT''S\n    ──────                      ─────────\n\n    ┌─────────────┐             ┌─────────────┐\n    │ Squamous    │             │░░░░░░░░░░░░░│ ← Columnar\n    │ (pink)      │             │░░░░░░░░░░░░░│   (salmon)\n    │             │             │             │\n    │             │             │             │\n    ├─────────────┤ Z-line      │░░░░░░░░░░░░░│\n    │ Columnar    │             │░░░░░░░░░░░░░│\n    │ (stomach)   │             ├─────────────┤\n    └─────────────┘             │ Columnar    │\n                                └─────────────┘\n\n    ⚠️ Requires INTESTINAL METAPLASIA on biopsy\n       (goblet cells) for diagnosis\n\n    PROGRESSION:\n    Barrett''s → Low-grade dysplasia → High-grade dysplasia → Adenocarcinoma\n       │              │                      │\n    Surveillance    ↑Surveillance        Ablation/Resection\n```\n\n### Cancer Risk in Barrett''s\n\n| Finding | Annual Cancer Risk |\n|---------|-------------------|\n| **Non-dysplastic Barrett''s** | 0.5% per year |\n| **Low-grade dysplasia** | 1-2% per year |\n| **High-grade dysplasia** | 5-10% per year |\n\n---\n\n## Medical Management\n\n### Lifestyle Modifications\n\n| Modification | Evidence |\n|--------------|----------|\n| **Weight loss** | Strong - reduces symptoms |\n| **Elevate head of bed** | Moderate - for nocturnal symptoms |\n| **Avoid late meals** | Moderate - 3 hours before bed |\n| **Avoid trigger foods** | Weak - individualized |\n| **Smoking cessation** | Moderate - reduces LES pressure |\n| **Limit alcohol** | Weak - may help |\n\n### Pharmacological Therapy\n\n#### Proton Pump Inhibitors (PPIs)\n\n```\n    PPI MECHANISM\n    ═════════════\n\n    Parietal Cell:\n\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                                         │\n    │   H+/K+-ATPase ────► H+ into lumen      │\n    │        ▲                                │\n    │        │                                │\n    │        ✕ ← PPI (irreversible block)     │\n    │                                         │\n    │   Proton pump is IRREVERSIBLY inhibited │\n    │   New pumps must be synthesized         │\n    │                                         │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n    Key points:\n    • Take 30-60 min before meals (pumps active when stimulated)\n    • Once daily often sufficient\n    • Twice daily for erosive esophagitis or EoE\n```\n\n| PPI | Standard Dose | Notes |\n|-----|---------------|-------|\n| **Omeprazole** | 20 mg daily | OTC available |\n| **Esomeprazole** | 20-40 mg daily | S-isomer |\n| **Pantoprazole** | 40 mg daily | Fewer drug interactions |\n| **Lansoprazole** | 30 mg daily | - |\n| **Rabeprazole** | 20 mg daily | - |\n\n#### Other Medications\n\n| Drug Class | Example | Use |\n|------------|---------|-----|\n| **H2 blockers** | Famotidine | Nocturnal acid breakthrough |\n| **Antacids** | Tums, Maalox | Acute relief |\n| **Prokinetics** | Metoclopramide | Gastroparesis component |\n| **Baclofen** | GABA-B agonist | Reduces TLESRs (refractory) |\n\n---\n\n## Surgical Management\n\n### Indications for Surgery\n\n| Indication | Details |\n|------------|---------|\n| **Refractory to medical therapy** | Symptoms despite optimal PPI |\n| **Patient preference** | Avoid lifelong medication |\n| **Volume regurgitation** | Not controlled by acid suppression |\n| **Medication intolerance** | PPI side effects |\n| **Large hiatal hernia** | Symptomatic Type II-IV |\n| **Documented GERD** | Must confirm with pH/impedance |\n\n> [!warning] Pre-operative Requirements\n> - **Confirm GERD**: pH monitoring (especially if no esophagitis)\n> - **Evaluate motility**: HRM to rule out achalasia, severe dysmotility\n> - **EGD**: Rule out Barrett''s, stricture, cancer\n> - **Appropriate expectations**: Surgery may not cure all symptoms\n\n### Pre-operative Evaluation\n\n```\n    PRE-FUNDOPLICATION WORKUP\n    ═════════════════════════\n\n    1. EGD\n       • Confirm no Barrett''s needing ablation first\n       • Grade esophagitis\n       • Rule out stricture, mass\n       • Assess hiatal hernia size\n\n    2. ESOPHAGEAL MANOMETRY (HRM)\n       • Rule out achalasia (fails to relax)\n       • Assess peristaltic function\n       • Guides wrap type:\n         - Normal motility → Nissen (360°)\n         - Poor motility → Toupet (270°)\n\n    3. 24-HOUR pH MONITORING\n       • Essential if no esophagitis on EGD\n       • Confirms pathologic reflux\n       • Correlates symptoms with reflux\n\n    4. BARIUM SWALLOW\n       • Optional\n       • Anatomy (hiatal hernia size, short esophagus)\n       • Stricture evaluation\n```\n\n### Surgical Options\n\nSee detailed note: [[Fundoplication]]\n\n| Procedure | Description | Best For |\n|-----------|-------------|----------|\n| **Nissen (360°)** | Complete wrap | Normal motility, best reflux control |\n| **Toupet (270°)** | Posterior partial | Impaired motility, redo |\n| **Dor (180°)** | Anterior partial | After Heller myotomy |\n| **LINX** | Magnetic sphincter | Alternative to fundoplication |\n\n### LINX Device\n\n```\n    LINX MAGNETIC SPHINCTER AUGMENTATION\n    ════════════════════════════════════\n\n    • Ring of magnetic titanium beads\n    • Placed around LES laparoscopically\n    • Beads separate with swallow pressure\n    • Close to prevent reflux\n\n          Rest                    Swallow\n         ─────                    ───────\n\n      ┌───●●●───┐              ┌───●─●─●───┐\n      │   LES   │       →      │    LES    │\n      │ closed  │              │   opens   │\n      └─────────┘              └───────────┘\n\n    Advantages: Preserves belch, reversible\n    Contraindications: Large hiatal hernia, Barrett''s\n```\n\n---\n\n## GERD vs Achalasia - Contrast\n\n```\n    LES DYSFUNCTION SPECTRUM\n    ════════════════════════\n\n                  ┌─────────────────────────────────┐\n                  │           NORMAL LES            │\n                  │    Pressure: 10-30 mmHg         │\n                  │    Relaxation: Complete         │\n                  └─────────────────────────────────┘\n                              │\n          ┌───────────────────┴───────────────────┐\n          ▼                                       ▼\n    ┌───────────────┐                     ┌───────────────┐\n    │     GERD      │                     │   ACHALASIA   │\n    ├───────────────┤                     ├───────────────┤\n    │ LES: LOW      │                     │ LES: HIGH     │\n    │ (<10 mmHg)    │                     │ (or normal)   │\n    │ or normal     │                     │               │\n    │               │                     │ Relaxation:   │\n    │ Relaxation:   │                     │ INCOMPLETE    │\n    │ COMPLETE      │                     │ (IRP >15)     │\n    │               │                     │               │\n    │ Problem:      │                     │ Problem:      │\n    │ Reflux UP     │                     │ Can''t pass    │\n    │               │                     │ DOWN          │\n    │ Symptoms:     │                     │ Symptoms:     │\n    │ Heartburn     │                     │ Dysphagia     │\n    │ Regurgitation │                     │ Regurgitation │\n    │               │                     │               │\n    │ Treatment:    │                     │ Treatment:    │\n    │ INCREASE LES  │                     │ DECREASE LES  │\n    │ (Fundoplication)│                   │ (Myotomy)     │\n    └───────────────┘                     └───────────────┘\n```\n\n---\n\n## Outcomes\n\n### Medical Therapy\n\n| Outcome | Rate |\n|---------|------|\n| **Symptom relief with PPI** | 70-80% |\n| **Healing of esophagitis (8 weeks)** | 85-95% |\n| **Long-term PPI dependence** | 50-80% relapse off PPI |\n\n### Surgical Therapy\n\n| Outcome | Rate |\n|---------|------|\n| **Symptom control at 5 years** | 85-90% |\n| **Off all acid suppression** | 70-80% |\n| **Need for redo surgery** | 5-10% |\n| **Post-op dysphagia (persistent)** | 3-5% |\n\n---\n\n## Follow-up and Surveillance\n\n### Non-Barrett''s GERD\n\n- No routine surveillance needed\n- Follow-up based on symptoms\n- Consider EGD if symptoms change\n\n### Barrett''s Esophagus Surveillance\n\n| Finding | Surveillance Interval |\n|---------|----------------------|\n| **Non-dysplastic** | EGD every 3-5 years |\n| **Low-grade dysplasia** | EGD every 6-12 months |\n| **High-grade dysplasia** | Endoscopic treatment (ablation/EMR) |\n\n---\n\n## Connections\n\n### Links to Other Concepts\n\n- **Pathophysiology**: [[LES Physiology]], [[Esophageal Anatomy]]\n- **Diagnosis**: [[Esophageal Manometry]]\n- **Treatment**: [[Fundoplication]]\n- **Complications**: [[Barrett''s Esophagus]], [[Esophageal Cancer]]\n- **Contrasts with**: [[03 Spaces/🔬 Active Projects/Learning Modules/Learning System/Study Library/02 - Concept Notes/Esophagus/Achalasia Cardia]] (opposite LES problem)\n- **Related procedures**: [[Heller Myotomy Technique]] (treats opposite problem)\n\n---\n\n## Quick Recall Questions\n\n1. Q: What is the most common mechanism of reflux in GERD?\n   A: Transient lower esophageal sphincter relaxations (TLESRs) - account for 50-70% of reflux episodes\n\n2. Q: What pH monitoring value confirms pathologic acid exposure?\n   A: Total acid exposure time >6% (time pH <4) or DeMeester score >14.7\n\n3. Q: When is esophageal manometry required before fundoplication?\n   A: Always - to rule out achalasia (would make reflux worse) and assess motility (guides wrap type - partial if poor motility)\n\n4. Q: What is the annual cancer risk in non-dysplastic Barrett''s esophagus?\n   A: Approximately 0.5% per year\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Shackelford Ch 7: *Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease*\n- Shackelford Ch 8: *Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease*\n- Shackelford Ch 9: *Barrett''s Esophagus*\n- Shackelford Ch 10: *Primary Antireflux Procedures*\n\n---\n\n*VPReFRE Checklist:*\n- [x] **V**isual: LA classification, pH monitoring diagrams\n- [x] **P**rocessed: Pathophysiology explained\n- [x] **Re**lational: Contrasted with achalasia\n- [x] **R**eflective: Clinical decision-making\n- [x] **E**fficient: Focused content","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
  '> Source: Shackelford Ch 7 - *Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux*, Ch 8 - *GERD*, Ch 9 - *Barrett''s Esophagus*, Ch 10 - *Antireflux Procedures*
