INSERT INTO atoms (title, slug, type, content, summary, specialty, system, topic, subtopic, tags, source_textbook, source_edition, source_chapter, difficulty, read_time_minutes, is_premium, is_published)
VALUES (
  'Heller Myotomy Technique',
  'surgery-esophagus-heller-myotomy-technique',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# Laparoscopic Heller Myotomy + Fundoplication\n\n> **Source**: Shackelford Ch 19 - *Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment*\n> **Topic System**: [[Esophagus Index]]\n> **Phase**: Shoot\n> **Tier**: 4 (Surgical Technique)\n\n---\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n> [!summary] One-liner\n> Laparoscopic Heller myotomy is the surgical division of LES circular muscle (6-8cm esophageal + 2-3cm gastric) combined with partial fundoplication (Dor/Toupet) for achalasia, achieving 90% long-term success.\n\n---\n\n## Indications & Contraindications\n\n### Indications\n\n| Indication | Notes |\n|------------|-------|\n| **Achalasia Type I, II** | First-line option |\n| **Achalasia Type III** | Extended myotomy; POEM may be preferred |\n| **Failed pneumatic dilation** | Rescue therapy |\n| **Patient preference** | Over PD or POEM |\n| **Young patients** | Better durability than PD |\n\n### Contraindications\n\n| Absolute | Relative |\n|----------|----------|\n| Unfit for general anesthesia | Prior POEM (can still do) |\n| Uncorrectable coagulopathy | Prior esophageal surgery |\n| End-stage sigmoid esophagus | Multiple prior Botox injections |\n\n---\n\n## Operative Technique\n\n### Setup\n\n```\n    PATIENT POSITIONING\n    ═══════════════════\n\n    • Supine, split-leg (French position)\n    • Arms tucked or extended\n    • Steep reverse Trendelenburg (30°)\n    • Surgeon between legs\n    • Assistant on patient''s left\n    • Camera holder on right\n```\n\n### Port Placement\n\n```\n    PORT PLACEMENT (5 ports)\n    ════════════════════════\n\n                    ┌─────┐\n                    │ 5mm │  Subxiphoid\n                    │Liver│  (liver retractor)\n                    │retr │\n                    └──┬──┘\n                       │\n         ┌─────┐   ┌───┴───┐   ┌─────┐\n         │ 5mm │   │ 10mm  │   │ 5mm │\n         │ LUQ │   │Umbil. │   │ RUQ │\n         │ L   │   │Camera │   │ R   │\n         └─────┘   └───────┘   └─────┘\n\n                    ┌─────┐\n                    │ 5mm │  Left lateral\n                    │Asst │  (assistant)\n                    └─────┘\n```\n\n### Step-by-Step Procedure\n\n#### Step 1-3: Exposure and Dissection\n\n1. Insert liver retractor via subxiphoid port\n2. Open gastrohepatic ligament (pars flaccida)\n3. Identify and preserve vagus nerves\n4. Mobilize distal esophagus circumferentially (5-6 cm)\n\n#### Step 4: Myotomy (CRITICAL)\n\n```\n    MYOTOMY TECHNIQUE\n    ═════════════════\n\n              6-8 cm\n          ◄────────────►\n    ┌─────────────────────────────┐\n    │                             │\n    │      ESOPHAGEAL             │\n    │      MYOTOMY                │\n    │                             │\n    │      Start here             │\n    │      (proximal esophagus)   │\n    │             │               │\n    │             ▼               │\n    │    Divide circular muscle   │\n    │    Preserve longitudinal    │\n    │    Expose mucosa (bulges)   │\n    │             │               │\n    ├─────────────┼───────────────┤ ← GEJ/Fat pad\n    │             │               │\n    │      GASTRIC                │  2-3 cm\n    │      EXTENSION              │  ◄──────►\n    │             │               │\n    │      MUST divide sling      │\n    │      fibers completely      │\n    │                             │\n    └─────────────────────────────┘\n\n    ⚠️ CRITICAL: Must extend onto gastric cardia\n       Incomplete distal myotomy = #1 cause of failure\n```\n\n**Myotomy Details**:\n\n| Parameter | Specification |\n|-----------|---------------|\n| **Location** | Anterior (11 o''clock) |\n| **Esophageal length** | 6-8 cm above GEJ |\n| **Gastric length** | **2-3 cm onto cardia** (CRITICAL) |\n| **Muscle divided** | Circular (inner) completely |\n| **Muscle preserved** | Longitudinal (outer) |\n| **Endpoint** | Mucosa bulges through |\n\n#### Step 5: Test for Mucosal Perforation\n\n```\n1. Fill abdomen with saline (submerge GEJ)\n2. Instill air via NG tube (or endoscope)\n3. Watch for bubbles at myotomy site\n4. If bubbles → identify and repair perforation\n5. Alternatively: Inject methylene blue\n```\n\n#### Step 6: Fundoplication\n\n**Choice of Fundoplication**:\n\n| Type | Configuration | Use When |\n|------|---------------|----------|\n| **Dor (Anterior 180°)** | Fundus folded over anterior myotomy | **Preferred** - covers myotomy |\n| **Toupet (Posterior 270°)** | Fundus wrapped posteriorly | Alternative - keeps edges apart |\n\n> [!warning] Avoid Nissen (360°)\n> Full wrap is too tight for aperistaltic esophagus → dysphagia\n\n**Dor Fundoplication Technique**:\n\n```\n    DOR FUNDOPLICATION\n    ═══════════════════\n\n           ┌─────────────┐\n           │   Myotomy   │\n           │   site      │\n           └──────┬──────┘\n                  │\n         ┌────────┴────────┐\n         │                 │\n    ┌────┴────┐       ┌────┴────┐\n    │ Left    │       │ Right   │\n    │ edge of │       │ edge of │\n    │ fundus  │       │ fundus  │\n    └────┬────┘       └────┬────┘\n         │                 │\n         │    FOLD OVER    │\n         │    MYOTOMY      │\n         │                 │\n         └────────┬────────┘\n                  │\n                  ▼\n         ┌─────────────────┐\n         │ Suture to       │\n         │ - Left & right  │\n         │   myotomy edges │\n         │ - Diaphragm     │\n         └─────────────────┘\n```\n\n---\n\n## Intraoperative Complications\n\n| Complication | Incidence | Management |\n|--------------|-----------|------------|\n| **Mucosal perforation** | 5-10% | Primary repair + Dor coverage |\n| **Bleeding** | <5% | Cautery, clips |\n| **Vagus injury** | <5% | May need pyloroplasty |\n| **Pleural entry** | Rare | Close defect, evacuate pneumothorax |\n\n### Managing Mucosal Perforation\n\n```\n1. Identify extent of injury\n2. Primary repair with absorbable suture (4-0 Vicryl)\n3. Interrupted sutures, mucosa-to-mucosa\n4. Test repair (air/saline)\n5. Complete Dor fundoplication (covers repair)\n6. Post-op: Gastrografin swallow POD1\n```\n\n---\n\n## Post-operative Care\n\n### Diet Advancement\n\n| Day | Diet |\n|-----|------|\n| POD1 | Gastrografin swallow → Clear liquids |\n| POD2 | Full liquids → Discharge |\n| Week 1-2 | Soft/puree diet |\n| Week 2-4 | Gradual advancement |\n| Week 4+ | Regular diet |\n\n---\n\n## Outcomes\n\n### Success Rates\n\n| Outcome | Rate |\n|---------|------|\n| **Initial symptom relief** | 90-95% |\n| **5-year success** | 85-90% |\n| **10-year success** | 80-85% |\n| **Need for reoperation** | <10% |\n\n### By Achalasia Type\n\n| Type | Success Rate | Notes |\n|------|--------------|-------|\n| Type I | 85-90% | Good response |\n| Type II | >90% | **Best outcomes** |\n| Type III | 70-80% | May need longer myotomy (consider POEM) |\n\n### GERD After Heller\n\n| With Fundoplication | GERD Rate |\n|---------------------|-----------|\n| Dor (anterior 180°) | 10-15% |\n| Toupet (posterior 270°) | 10-15% |\n| No fundoplication | 30-50% |\n\n---\n\n## Connections\n\n### Links to Other Concepts\n\n- **Prerequisite**: [[03 Spaces/🔬 Active Projects/Learning Modules/Learning System/Study Library/02 - Concept Notes/Esophagus/Achalasia Cardia]], [[Esophageal Manometry]]\n- **Alternative procedures**: [[POEM Procedure]], Pneumatic Dilation\n- **Related techniques**: [[Fundoplication]]\n- **Comparison**: [[Achalasia - LHM vs POEM]]\n- **Anatomy**: [[Esophageal Anatomy]], [[LES Physiology]]\n\n---\n\n## Quick Recall Questions\n\n1. Q: What is the critical myotomy length onto the gastric cardia?\n   A: 2-3 cm onto the stomach; incomplete distal extension is the #1 cause of failure\n\n2. Q: Why is Dor fundoplication preferred over Nissen?\n   A: Dor (anterior 180°) covers the myotomy site (protects against leak) and is a partial wrap suitable for aperistaltic esophagus. Nissen (360°) is too tight → dysphagia\n\n3. Q: What is the management of intraoperative mucosal perforation?\n   A: Primary repair with absorbable suture + complete Dor fundoplication to cover the repair + post-op contrast study\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Shackelford Ch 19: *Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment*\n\n---\n\n*VPReFRE Checklist:*\n- [x] **V**isual: Port placement, myotomy diagram\n- [x] **P**rocessed: Step-by-step technique\n- [x] **Re**lational: Connected to achalasia, alternatives\n- [x] **R**eflective: Complications and management\n- [x] **E**fficient: Focused on technique","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
  '> Source: Shackelford Ch 19 - *Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment*
> Topic System: [[Esophagus Index]]
> Phase: Shoot
> Tier: 4 (Surgical Technique)',
