INSERT INTO atoms (title, slug, type, content, summary, specialty, system, topic, subtopic, tags, source_textbook, source_edition, source_chapter, difficulty, read_time_minutes, is_premium, is_published)
VALUES (
  'LES Physiology',
  'surgery-esophagus-les-physiology',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# Lower Esophageal Sphincter (LES) Physiology\n\n> **Source**: Shackelford Ch 1 - *Anatomy of the Esophagus*, Ch 7 - *Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux*\n> **Topic System**: [[Esophagus Index]]\n> **Phase**: Shoot\n> **Tier**: 1 (Foundation)\n\n---\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n> [!summary] One-liner\n> The LES is a 3-4 cm high-pressure zone of tonically contracted smooth muscle that relaxes with swallowing via NO/VIP release, augmented by the crural diaphragm—failure causes GERD (hypotensive) or achalasia (fails to relax).\n\n---\n\n## Anatomical Components\n\n### The Anti-Reflux Barrier\n\n```\n    COMPONENTS OF GE JUNCTION BARRIER\n    ══════════════════════════════════\n\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                                                 │\n    │   1. INTRINSIC LES                              │\n    │      • Thickened circular smooth muscle         │\n    │      • 3-4 cm length                            │\n    │      • Tonic contraction (10-30 mmHg)           │\n    │                                                 │\n    │   2. EXTRINSIC (CRURAL DIAPHRAGM)               │\n    │      • Right crus forms sling                   │\n    │      • Pinchcock effect on inspiration          │\n    │      • Contributes ~50% of barrier              │\n    │                                                 │\n    │   3. PHRENOESOPHAGEAL LIGAMENT                  │\n    │      • Anchors esophagus to diaphragm           │\n    │      • Prevents excessive movement              │\n    │                                                 │\n    │   4. INTRA-ABDOMINAL ESOPHAGUS                  │\n    │      • 1-2 cm below diaphragm                   │\n    │      • Positive pressure environment            │\n    │      • Compressed by increased IAP              │\n    │                                                 │\n    │   5. ANGLE OF HIS                               │\n    │      • Acute angle at cardia                    │\n    │      • Creates mucosal flap valve               │\n    │                                                 │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### LES Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Normal Value | Clinical Significance |\n|-----------|--------------|----------------------|\n| **Resting pressure** | 10-30 mmHg | <10 = hypotensive (GERD risk) |\n| **Length** | 3-4 cm | <2 cm = mechanically defective |\n| **Intra-abdominal length** | 1-2 cm | <1 cm = herniated |\n| **Relaxation** | To gastric baseline | Incomplete = achalasia |\n| **IRP (on HRM)** | <15 mmHg | >15 = impaired relaxation |\n\n---\n\n## Neural Control\n\n### Resting Tone (Tonic Contraction)\n\n```\n    LES RESTING TONE MAINTENANCE\n    ════════════════════════════\n\n    MYOGENIC (Intrinsic)\n    ├── Spontaneous smooth muscle tone\n    └── Ca2+ influx → contraction\n\n    NEUROGENIC\n    ├── Excitatory input (maintains tone)\n    │   └── Cholinergic (ACh) from vagus\n    │\n    └── Inhibitory input (modulates)\n        └── NANC neurons (NO, VIP)\n\n    HORMONAL\n    ├── Increase tone: Gastrin, motilin\n    └── Decrease tone: CCK, secretin, progesterone\n```\n\n### LES Relaxation (Swallow-Initiated)\n\n```\n    SWALLOW-INDUCED LES RELAXATION\n    ═══════════════════════════════\n\n    Swallow initiated\n          │\n          ▼\n    Swallowing center (medulla)\n          │\n          ▼\n    Vagal efferent (dorsal motor nucleus)\n          │\n          ▼\n    Myenteric plexus at LES\n          │\n          ├────────────────────────────┐\n          ▼                            ▼\n    INHIBITORY neurons           EXCITATORY neurons\n    (predominate during          (suppressed)\n     relaxation)\n          │\n          ▼\n    Release NO + VIP\n          │\n          ▼\n    Smooth muscle relaxation\n    (↓ Ca2+, ↑ K+ channels)\n          │\n          ▼\n    LES OPENS → Food passes\n          │\n          ▼\n    After bolus: Tone restored\n```\n\n> [!tip] Clinical Pearl - Achalasia Connection\n> In **achalasia**, the inhibitory neurons (NO, VIP) are **lost**. Without them:\n> - Swallow signal arrives but relaxation doesn''t occur\n> - Excitatory input (ACh) is unopposed\n> - LES remains contracted → dysphagia\n\n---\n\n## Transient LES Relaxations (TLESRs)\n\n### Definition and Mechanism\n\nTLESRs are spontaneous LES relaxations **not triggered by swallowing**, lasting 10-60 seconds.\n\n```\n    TRANSIENT LES RELAXATION (TLESR)\n    ═════════════════════════════════\n\n    TRIGGER: Gastric distension\n             │\n             ▼\n    Vagal afferents (from stomach)\n             │\n             ▼\n    Brainstem reflex center\n             │\n             ▼\n    Vagal efferent to LES\n             │\n             ▼\n    TLESR (without swallow)\n             │\n             ▼\n    Purpose: VENTING (belching)\n\n    ⚠️ PROBLEM: Main mechanism of reflux in GERD\n       Acid can reflux during TLESR\n```\n\n### TLESR vs Swallow-Induced Relaxation\n\n| Feature | Swallow-Induced | TLESR |\n|---------|-----------------|-------|\n| **Trigger** | Swallow | Gastric distension |\n| **Duration** | 5-10 seconds | 10-60 seconds |\n| **Crural inhibition** | No | Yes (diaphragm relaxes too) |\n| **Purpose** | Allow bolus passage | Venting (belch) |\n| **Role in GERD** | Minor | **Major** (50-70% of reflux) |\n\n---\n\n## Factors Affecting LES Pressure\n\n### Factors That INCREASE LES Pressure\n\n| Factor | Mechanism |\n|--------|-----------|\n| **Protein meal** | Gastrin release |\n| **Gastrin** | Direct smooth muscle effect |\n| **Motilin** | Increases tone |\n| **Metoclopramide** | Dopamine antagonist, ↑ ACh |\n| **α-adrenergic agonists** | Smooth muscle contraction |\n| **Increased IAP** | Compresses intra-abdominal segment |\n\n### Factors That DECREASE LES Pressure\n\n| Factor | Mechanism |\n|--------|-----------|\n| **Fat meal** | CCK release |\n| **Chocolate** | Methylxanthines → ↓ tone |\n| **Caffeine** | Same as chocolate |\n| **Alcohol** | Direct smooth muscle relaxation |\n| **Smoking** | ↓ LES pressure |\n| **Peppermint** | Smooth muscle relaxation |\n| **CCK, Secretin** | Hormonal |\n| **Progesterone** | Smooth muscle relaxation (pregnancy) |\n| **Nitrates** | NO donors |\n| **Calcium channel blockers** | ↓ Ca2+ influx |\n| **Anticholinergics** | ↓ excitatory input |\n| **Morphine** | Variable, generally ↓ |\n\n---\n\n## LES Dysfunction States\n\n### Comparison of LES Disorders\n\n```\n    LES DYSFUNCTION SPECTRUM\n    ════════════════════════\n\n    NORMAL                    GERD                      ACHALASIA\n    ──────                    ────                      ─────────\n\n    Pressure: 10-30 mmHg      Pressure: LOW (<10)       Pressure: HIGH (>30)\n                              or normal with ↑TLESRs    or normal\n\n    Relaxation: Complete      Relaxation: Complete      Relaxation: INCOMPLETE\n    (to gastric baseline)     (to gastric baseline)     (IRP >15 mmHg)\n\n    Result:                   Result:                   Result:\n    Normal function           Acid reflux               Dysphagia\n                              Heartburn                 Regurgitation\n```\n\n### GERD: LES Incompetence\n\n| Mechanism | Prevalence in GERD |\n|-----------|-------------------|\n| **Transient LES relaxations** | 50-70% (most common) |\n| **Hypotensive LES** | 20-30% |\n| **Anatomical disruption** (hiatal hernia) | 40-60% |\n\n### Achalasia: Failed LES Relaxation\n\n| Finding | Normal | Achalasia |\n|---------|--------|-----------|\n| **IRP** | <15 mmHg | **>15 mmHg** |\n| **Basal LES pressure** | 10-30 mmHg | Often elevated |\n| **Relaxation** | Complete | **Incomplete** |\n| **Cause** | - | Loss of NO/VIP neurons |\n\n---\n\n## Crural Diaphragm Contribution\n\n### Dual Sphincter Concept\n\n```\n    THE DUAL SPHINCTER\n    ══════════════════\n\n              ┌──────────────────────────────────┐\n              │                                  │\n    At REST   │   LES ════════════════ 50%      │\n              │   Crural diaphragm ═══ 50%      │\n              │                                  │\n              └──────────────────────────────────┘\n\n    During INSPIRATION:\n    • LES: Unchanged\n    • Crural: INCREASES (contracts with diaphragm)\n    • Protects against reflux when IAP rises\n\n    During SWALLOW:\n    • LES: Relaxes (NO/VIP)\n    • Crural: ALSO inhibited\n    • Both must relax for bolus to pass\n\n    In HIATAL HERNIA:\n    • LES: Displaced above diaphragm\n    • Crural: No longer augments LES\n    • Loss of dual sphincter protection\n```\n\n---\n\n## Clinical Applications\n\n### Pharmacological Targets\n\n| Drug | Mechanism | Use |\n|------|-----------|-----|\n| **Baclofen** | GABA-B agonist, ↓ TLESRs | Refractory GERD |\n| **Metoclopramide** | ↑ LES pressure, prokinetic | GERD, gastroparesis |\n| **Nitrates/CCBs** | ↓ LES pressure | Achalasia (temporizing) |\n| **Botox** | Blocks ACh at LES | Achalasia (high-risk patients) |\n\n### Surgical Relevance\n\n| Procedure | Effect on LES |\n|-----------|---------------|\n| **Fundoplication** | Augments LES, creates valve |\n| **Heller myotomy** | Disrupts LES (for achalasia) |\n| **POEM** | Divides LES circular muscle |\n| **Hiatal hernia repair** | Restores crural contribution |\n\n---\n\n## Connections\n\n### Links to Other Concepts\n\n- **Prerequisite**: [[Esophageal Anatomy]]\n- **Builds upon**: Smooth muscle physiology, autonomic innervation\n- **Leads to**: [[GERD]], [[03 Spaces/🔬 Active Projects/Learning Modules/Learning System/Study Library/02 - Concept Notes/Esophagus/Achalasia Cardia]], [[Fundoplication]]\n- **Related procedures**: [[Heller Myotomy Technique]], [[POEM Procedure]]\n\n---\n\n## Quick Recall Questions\n\n1. Q: What are the two main neurotransmitters responsible for LES relaxation?\n   A: Nitric oxide (NO) and vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP)\n\n2. Q: What is the most common mechanism of reflux in GERD?\n   A: Transient LES relaxations (TLESRs) - account for 50-70% of reflux episodes\n\n3. Q: Why does hiatal hernia promote GERD?\n   A: Loss of crural diaphragm contribution (no longer augments LES) + loss of positive pressure on intra-abdominal esophagus\n\n4. Q: What is the IRP cutoff for impaired LES relaxation?\n   A: IRP >15 mmHg indicates impaired relaxation (suggestive of achalasia)\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Shackelford Ch 1: *Anatomy of the Esophagus and the Gastroesophageal Reflux Barrier*\n- Shackelford Ch 7: *Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux*\n\n---\n\n*VPReFRE Checklist:*\n- [x] **V**isual: Contains diagrams\n- [x] **P**rocessed: In own words\n- [x] **Re**lational: Connected to GERD, achalasia\n- [x] **R**eflective: Clinical applications\n- [x] **E**fficient: Focused content","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
  '> Source: Shackelford Ch 1 - *Anatomy of the Esophagus*, Ch 7 - *Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux*
