INSERT INTO atoms (title, slug, type, content, summary, specialty, system, topic, subtopic, tags, source_textbook, source_edition, source_chapter, difficulty, read_time_minutes, is_premium, is_published)
VALUES (
  'POEM Procedure',
  'surgery-esophagus-poem-procedure',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# POEM - Peroral Endoscopic Myotomy\n\n> **Source**: Shackelford Ch 19 - *Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment*\n> **Topic System**: [[Esophagus Index]]\n> **Phase**: Shoot\n> **Tier**: 4 (Surgical Technique)\n\n---\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n> [!summary] One-liner\n> POEM is an incisionless endoscopic myotomy for achalasia performed through a submucosal tunnel, allowing longer myotomies (ideal for Type III), but with higher GERD rates (20-50%) due to lack of fundoplication.\n\n---\n\n## Indications & Advantages\n\n### Indications\n\n| Indication | Notes |\n|------------|-------|\n| **Achalasia Type I, II** | Equivalent to LHM |\n| **Achalasia Type III** | **Preferred** - longer myotomy possible |\n| **Failed prior LHM** | Can approach from opposite side (posterior) |\n| **Sigmoid achalasia** | Technically easier than redo surgery |\n| **Patient preference** | Incisionless approach |\n\n### POEM Advantages Over Heller\n\n| Feature | POEM | Heller |\n|---------|------|--------|\n| **Incisions** | None | 5 ports |\n| **Myotomy length** | Flexible (10-25 cm possible) | Standard 6-8 cm |\n| **Approach** | Anterior or posterior | Anterior only |\n| **Type III suitability** | Excellent | Suboptimal |\n| **Recovery** | Faster | Slightly longer |\n| **Redo capability** | Can use opposite side | Limited |\n\n### POEM Disadvantages\n\n| Disadvantage | Details |\n|--------------|---------|\n| **Higher GERD** | 20-50% (no fundoplication) |\n| **Requires expertise** | Steep learning curve |\n| **Long-term data** | Limited (10 years max) |\n| **Gas complications** | Pneumomediastinum, pneumoperitoneum |\n\n---\n\n## Operative Technique\n\n### Setup\n\n```\n    POEM SETUP\n    ══════════\n\n    • General anesthesia with intubation\n    • Supine position\n    • CO2 insufflation (not air - absorbs faster)\n    • High-definition gastroscope with cap\n    • Electrosurgical generator (spray coag, soft coag)\n    • Coagulation forceps, injection needle\n    • Clips for closure\n```\n\n### Step-by-Step Procedure\n\n#### Step 1: Mucosal Entry\n\n```\n    MUCOSAL INCISION SITE\n    ═════════════════════\n\n    Location: 10-15 cm above GEJ\n    Position: Posterior (5-6 o''clock) or Anterior (2 o''clock)\n\n           10-15 cm above GEJ\n                  │\n                  ▼\n         ┌───────────────┐\n         │               │\n         │    ●          │ ← Mucosal incision\n         │  (entry)      │   (2 cm longitudinal)\n         │               │\n         │               │\n         │               │\n         └───────────────┘\n                  │\n                  ▼\n              Toward GEJ\n\n    Technique:\n    1. Submucosal injection (saline + methylene blue)\n    2. Create mucosal bleb\n    3. Incise mucosa longitudinally (2 cm)\n    4. Enter submucosal space\n```\n\n#### Step 2: Submucosal Tunnel\n\n```\n    SUBMUCOSAL TUNNELING\n    ═══════════════════\n\n              Entry ●\n                  │\n                  │  Tunnel created\n                  │  in submucosal\n                  │  plane\n                  │\n                  │  (Inject, spread,\n                  │   dissect)\n                  │\n              ────┼──── Diaphragm\n                  │\n                  │  Continue 2-3 cm\n                  │  onto gastric cardia\n                  │\n                  ▼\n              End of tunnel\n\n    Key Points:\n    • Use spray coagulation\n    • Inject saline to maintain plane\n    • Blue staining from methylene blue guides\n    • Tunnel must extend onto stomach (like Heller)\n```\n\n#### Step 3: Myotomy\n\n```\n    SELECTIVE CIRCULAR MYOTOMY\n    ══════════════════════════\n\n    Cross-sectional view:\n\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────┐\n    │         MUCOSA                  │ ← Intact (in tunnel)\n    ├─────────────────────────────────┤\n    │       SUBMUCOSA                 │ ← Tunnel space\n    ├─────────────────────────────────┤\n    │ ████ CIRCULAR MUSCLE ████       │ ← DIVIDED (myotomy)\n    ├─────────────────────────────────┤\n    │    Longitudinal muscle          │ ← PRESERVED\n    └─────────────────────────────────┘\n\n    Technique:\n    1. Identify circular muscle fibers (transverse)\n    2. Hook and coagulate fibers\n    3. Divide from proximal to distal\n    4. Preserve longitudinal muscle (usually)\n    5. Complete division at gastric cardia\n```\n\n**Myotomy Length**:\n\n| Achalasia Type | Recommended Length |\n|----------------|--------------------|\n| Type I, II | 6-10 cm esophageal + 2-3 cm gastric |\n| Type III | 10-20+ cm (extend to cover spastic segment) |\n\n#### Step 4: Mucosal Closure\n\n```\n    CLOSURE TECHNIQUES\n    ═══════════════════\n\n    1. ENDOCLIPS\n       • Multiple clips to approximate mucosal edges\n       • Most common method\n       • 5-10 clips typically\n\n    2. ENDOSCOPIC SUTURING\n       • OverStitch device\n       • More secure closure\n\n           ┌─●─●─●─●─●─┐\n           │   Clips   │\n           │   close   │\n           │   entry   │\n           └───────────┘\n```\n\n---\n\n## Post-operative Care\n\n### Immediate Management\n\n| Item | Protocol |\n|------|----------|\n| **Observation** | Monitor for chest pain, fever, subcutaneous emphysema |\n| **NPO** | Overnight |\n| **Imaging** | Gastrografin swallow POD1 |\n| **Antibiotics** | Continue 24-48 hours |\n| **PPI** | Start immediately (high GERD rates) |\n\n### Expected Gas-Related Findings\n\n| Finding | Management |\n|---------|------------|\n| **Subcutaneous emphysema** | Common, self-resolving |\n| **Pneumomediastinum** | Usually benign if no leak |\n| **Pneumoperitoneum** | Needle decompression if tense |\n| **Capnoperitoneum** | From CO2, resolves quickly |\n\n---\n\n## Complications\n\n### Post-operative\n\n| Complication | Incidence | Management |\n|--------------|-----------|------------|\n| **Pneumomediastinum** | 10-20% | Observe if stable |\n| **Pneumoperitoneum** | 5-10% | Needle decompression if tense |\n| **Leak** | 0.5-1% | NPO, antibiotics, drainage, stent |\n| **GERD** | **20-50%** | PPI, may need late fundoplication |\n| **Delayed bleeding** | <1% | Endoscopic hemostasis |\n\n> [!warning] GERD After POEM\n> Unlike Heller (with fundoplication), POEM has **no anti-reflux procedure**\n> - GERD rate: 20-50%\n> - All patients should be on PPI\n> - May need fundoplication later if severe\n\n---\n\n## Outcomes\n\n### Success Rates\n\n| Outcome | Rate |\n|---------|------|\n| **Initial clinical success** | 90-98% |\n| **2-3 year success** | 90-95% |\n| **5-year success** | ~85-90% |\n\n### By Achalasia Type\n\n| Type | Success Rate | Notes |\n|------|--------------|-------|\n| Type I | 90-95% | Excellent |\n| Type II | 95%+ | Best |\n| Type III | **85-90%** | Better than Heller for this type |\n\n### POEM vs Heller Head-to-Head\n\n| Outcome | POEM | Heller |\n|---------|------|--------|\n| Short-term symptom relief | 95% | 93% |\n| 2-year clinical success | 92% | 90% |\n| GERD (objective) | 44% | 29% |\n| Serious adverse events | 3% | 3% |\n\n---\n\n## Special Situations\n\n### POEM After Failed Heller\n\n- Approach from **posterior** (opposite to prior anterior myotomy)\n- Tunnel through unscarred tissue\n- Success rate: 80-90%\n\n### POEM for Type III Achalasia\n\n- **Preferred over Heller** for Type III\n- Can extend myotomy 15-20 cm or more\n- Address entire spastic segment\n- Improved chest pain relief\n\n---\n\n## Connections\n\n### Links to Other Concepts\n\n- **Prerequisite**: [[03 Spaces/🔬 Active Projects/Learning Modules/Learning System/Study Library/02 - Concept Notes/Esophagus/Achalasia Cardia]], [[Esophageal Manometry]]\n- **Alternative procedure**: [[Heller Myotomy Technique]]\n- **Comparison**: [[Achalasia - LHM vs POEM]]\n- **Complication**: [[GERD]]\n- **May need later**: [[Fundoplication]]\n\n---\n\n## Quick Recall Questions\n\n1. Q: What is the main advantage of POEM for Type III achalasia?\n   A: Can perform a longer myotomy (10-20+ cm) to address the entire spastic segment\n\n2. Q: What is the main disadvantage of POEM compared to Heller?\n   A: Higher GERD rates (20-50%) because no fundoplication is performed\n\n3. Q: How do you approach a failed Heller with POEM?\n   A: Perform POEM from the posterior approach (opposite side from the anterior Heller myotomy)\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Shackelford Ch 19: *Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment*\n- Inoue H et al. Peroral Endoscopic Myotomy (POEM) for Esophageal Achalasia. Endoscopy 2010\n\n---\n\n*VPReFRE Checklist:*\n- [x] **V**isual: Tunnel and myotomy diagrams\n- [x] **P**rocessed: Step-by-step technique\n- [x] **Re**lational: Compared to Heller\n- [x] **R**eflective: Complications addressed\n- [x] **E**fficient: Focused content","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
  '> Source: Shackelford Ch 19 - *Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment*
> Topic System: [[Esophagus Index]]
> Phase: Shoot
> Tier: 4 (Surgical Technique)',
