INSERT INTO atoms (title, slug, type, content, summary, specialty, system, topic, subtopic, tags, source_textbook, source_edition, source_chapter, difficulty, read_time_minutes, is_premium, is_published)
VALUES (
  'Surgical Management of GERD',
  'surgery-esophagus-surgical-management-of-gerd',
  'concept',
  '{"markdown":"# Surgical Management of GERD\n\n## Overview\n\nGastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) affects 10-20% of adults in Western populations. While most patients respond to lifestyle modifications and medical therapy, approximately 30-40% require long-term PPI use, and 10-15% may benefit from surgical intervention. Anti-reflux surgery (ARS), primarily laparoscopic fundoplication, remains the definitive treatment for appropriately selected patients.\n\n```\nANTI-REFLUX BARRIER - ANATOMY\n═════════════════════════════\n\nNormal Anti-Reflux Mechanisms:\n\n    Esophagus\n        │\n        │   1. LES intrinsic tone (10-35 mmHg)\n        │\n    ╔═══╧═══╗ ←── 2. Acute angle of His\n    ║  LES  ║\n    ╚═══╤═══╝\n        │     ←── 3. Phrenoesophageal ligament\n    ════╪════     (anchors esophagus)\n        │\n    ┌───┴───┐ ←── 4. Crural diaphragm\n    │       │     (external sphincter)\n    │Stomach│\n    │       │ ←── 5. Intra-abdominal esophagus\n    └───────┘     (positive pressure segment)\n\nFailure of any component → GERD\nFundoplication recreates/augments these mechanisms\n```\n\n---\n\n## Pathophysiology of GERD\n\n### Mechanisms of Reflux\n\n```\nGERD PATHOPHYSIOLOGY\n════════════════════\n\nPRIMARY MECHANISMS:\n─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n1. Transient LES Relaxations (TLESRs)\n   • Most common mechanism (50-70%)\n   • Physiologic but excessive\n   • Not related to swallowing\n\n2. Hypotensive LES\n   • Resting pressure <10 mmHg\n   • Scleroderma, post-myotomy\n\n3. Anatomic disruption\n   • Hiatal hernia\n   • Loss of angle of His\n   • Short intra-abdominal esophagus\n\nCONTRIBUTING FACTORS:\n─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n• Impaired esophageal clearance\n• Delayed gastric emptying\n• Increased intra-abdominal pressure (obesity)\n• Diet/lifestyle factors\n• Medications (CCB, nitrates, anticholinergics)\n```\n\n### Hiatal Hernia Classification\n\n```\nHIATAL HERNIA TYPES\n═══════════════════\n\nTYPE I (Sliding) - 95%           TYPE II (Paraesophageal)\n────────────────────             ─────────────────────────\n        │                               │\n    ════╪════                       ════╪════\n        │                               │ ┌───┐\n    ┌───┴───┐                       ┌───┴─│ F │\n    │  EGJ  │ ← Above               │ EGJ │ u │\n    │       │   diaphragm           │     │ n │\n    └───────┘                       └─────│ d │\n                                          │ u │\n    GEJ migrates                          │ s │\n    into thorax                           └───┘\n                                    Fundus herniates\n                                    beside esophagus\n\nTYPE III (Mixed)                 TYPE IV (Complex)\n────────────────                 ─────────────────\n    Combined                     Other organs herniate\n    Type I + II                  (colon, spleen, omentum)\n    Most common                  Highest risk\n    large hernia\n```\n\n---\n\n## Indications for Anti-Reflux Surgery\n\n### Established Indications\n\n```\nINDICATIONS FOR ANTI-REFLUX SURGERY\n═══════════════════════════════════\n\nDEFINITE INDICATIONS:\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ 1. Refractory to medical therapy                        │\n│    • Persistent symptoms despite optimal PPI            │\n│    • Must confirm ongoing reflux (pH study)            │\n│                                                         │\n│ 2. PPI-responsive but desires surgery                  │\n│    • Long-term PPI concerns                            │\n│    • Medication non-compliance                          │\n│    • Quality of life preference                         │\n│                                                         │\n│ 3. Large hiatal hernia                                  │\n│    • Type II, III, IV (paraesophageal)                │\n│    • Symptomatic Type I >5 cm                          │\n│                                                         │\n│ 4. Extra-esophageal manifestations                      │\n│    • Recurrent aspiration                              │\n│    • Chronic laryngitis                                │\n│    • Asthma exacerbated by reflux                      │\n│                                                         │\n│ 5. Barrett''s with intractable symptoms                 │\n│    (does NOT prevent progression to cancer)            │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nRELATIVE INDICATIONS:\n• Young patients facing lifelong PPI\n• Volume regurgitation despite PPI\n• Medication side effects\n```\n\n### Pre-operative Evaluation\n\n| Test | Purpose | Key Findings |\n|------|---------|--------------|\n| **EGD** | Mucosal assessment | Esophagitis grade, Barrett''s, stricture, mass |\n| **pH/Impedance** | Confirm reflux | DeMeester >14.7, AET >6% |\n| **HRM** | Motility assessment | Rule out achalasia, assess peristalsis |\n| **Barium swallow** | Anatomy | Hernia size, esophageal length |\n| **Gastric emptying** | Gastroparesis | If delayed, consider pyloroplasty |\n\n```\nPRE-OPERATIVE ALGORITHM\n═══════════════════════\n\nSuspected GERD candidate\n         │\n         ▼\n┌─────────────────────┐\n│        EGD          │ → Document esophagitis\n│                     │   Rule out Barrett''s/mass\n└──────────┬──────────┘   Biopsy if indicated\n           │\n           ▼\n┌─────────────────────┐\n│  Esophageal HRM     │ → Rule out achalasia\n│                     │   Assess peristalsis\n└──────────┬──────────┘   (impacts wrap choice)\n           │\n           ▼\n┌─────────────────────┐\n│ 24-hour pH/Impedance│ → Confirm pathological reflux\n│                     │   DeMeester score\n└──────────┬──────────┘   Symptom correlation\n           │\n    ┌──────┴──────┐\n    │             │\nConfirmed     Not confirmed\nreflux        reflux\n    │             │\n    ▼             ▼\nSurgery      Reconsider\nindicated    diagnosis\n```\n\n---\n\n## Surgical Options\n\n### Fundoplication Types\n\n```\nFUNDOPLICATION COMPARISON\n═════════════════════════\n\nNISSEN (360° TOTAL)              TOUPET (270° POSTERIOR)\n────────────────────             ───────────────────────\n\n    Esophagus                        Esophagus\n        │                                │\n   ┌────┴────┐                      ╱────┴────╲\n   │ ╭─────╮ │                    ╱            ╲\n   │ │     │ │                   │              │\n   │ │ Eso │ │                   │     Eso     │\n   │ │     │ │                   │              │\n   │ ╰─────╯ │                    ╲            ╱\n   └─────────┘                      ╲────┬────╱\n                                        │\n\n• Complete wrap               • Partial posterior wrap\n• Best reflux control         • Less dysphagia\n• Higher dysphagia           • Used with weak motility\n• Standard for normal        • Good reflux control\n  motility\n\n\nDOR (180° ANTERIOR)              WATSON (120° ANTERIOR)\n───────────────────              ─────────────────────\n\n    Esophagus                        Esophagus\n        │                                │\n   ┌────┴────┐                      ────┴────\n   │ ╭─────╮ │                     ╭─────╮\n   │ │     │                       │     │\n   │ │ Eso │                       │ Eso │\n   │ │     │                       │     │\n   │ ╰─────╯                       ╰─────╯\n   └─────────\n\n• Partial anterior wrap      • Minimal wrap\n• Used with myotomy          • Rarely used alone\n  (Heller procedure)         • Lowest dysphagia\n• Covers myotomy site        • Lowest reflux control\n```\n\n### Selection Criteria\n\n| Patient Factor | Recommended Wrap |\n|---------------|------------------|\n| Normal peristalsis | Nissen (360°) |\n| Weak peristalsis (IEM) | Toupet (270°) |\n| Very weak/absent motility | Dor (180°) or Toupet |\n| Post-myotomy (achalasia) | Dor (180°) |\n| Failed prior Nissen | Toupet or Dor |\n| Morbid obesity | Consider RYGB instead |\n\n---\n\n## Laparoscopic Nissen Fundoplication\n\n### Surgical Technique\n\n```\nLAPAROSCOPIC NISSEN - KEY STEPS\n═══════════════════════════════\n\nPOSITION: Supine, split-leg, reverse Trendelenburg (15-20°)\n\nPORT PLACEMENT:\n     ┌─────────────────────────┐\n     │          ○              │  Camera (10-12mm)\n     │         /│\\             │\n     │        / │ \\            │\n     │       ○  │  ○           │  Working ports (5mm)\n     │      /   │   \\          │\n     │     ○    │    ○         │  Liver retractor + Assistant\n     └─────────────────────────┘\n\nCRITICAL STEPS:\n\n1. HIATAL DISSECTION\n   ┌───────────────────────────────────────────┐\n   │ • Divide gastrohepatic ligament          │\n   │ • Identify right crus                     │\n   │ • Dissect posterior to esophagus         │\n   │ • Identify left crus                      │\n   │ • Create retroesophageal window          │\n   │ • Preserve vagus nerves                   │\n   └───────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n2. FUNDIC MOBILIZATION\n   ┌───────────────────────────────────────────┐\n   │ • Divide short gastric vessels           │\n   │ • Mobilize fundus completely              │\n   │ • Ensure \"floppy\" fundus                 │\n   │ • No tension on wrap                      │\n   └───────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n3. CRURAL CLOSURE\n   ┌───────────────────────────────────────────┐\n   │ • Approximate crura posteriorly          │\n   │ • Non-absorbable sutures (0 silk/Ethibond)│\n   │ • Snug but not tight                      │\n   │ • Mesh if large defect (controversial)   │\n   └───────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n4. FUNDOPLICATION\n   ┌───────────────────────────────────────────┐\n   │ • Pass fundus posterior to esophagus     │\n   │ • \"Shoeshine\" maneuver to confirm        │\n   │ • Create 2-3 cm wrap                      │\n   │ • Include esophageal wall in sutures     │\n   │ • 50-56 Fr bougie for calibration        │\n   │ • 2-3 sutures (non-absorbable)           │\n   └───────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### The \"Floppy Nissen\" Principles\n\n```\nFLOPPY NISSEN - KEY PRINCIPLES\n══════════════════════════════\n\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                                              │\n    │  1. SHORT WRAP: 2-3 cm (not >3 cm)          │\n    │     • Longer wrap = more dysphagia          │\n    │                                              │\n    │  2. TENSION-FREE                             │\n    │     • Complete fundic mobilization          │\n    │     • Divide all short gastrics             │\n    │                                              │\n    │  3. CALIBRATED                               │\n    │     • 50-56 Fr bougie during construction   │\n    │     • Prevents too-tight wrap               │\n    │                                              │\n    │  4. FUNDUS-TO-FUNDUS                         │\n    │     • True fundus wraps around              │\n    │     • Not body of stomach                   │\n    │     • \"Shoeshine\" confirms proper position  │\n    │                                              │\n    │  5. SECURE TO ESOPHAGUS                      │\n    │     • Include esophageal muscle in sutures  │\n    │     • Prevents slippage                      │\n    │                                              │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Intraoperative Verification\n\n| Maneuver | Purpose |\n|----------|---------|\n| \"Shoeshine\" test | Confirm fundus passes freely |\n| Bougie placement | Calibrate wrap tightness |\n| Intraoperative EGD | Verify wrap position, no twist |\n| Retroflexion view | Confirm symmetric wrap |\n\n---\n\n## Toupet (Partial Posterior) Fundoplication\n\n### Technique\n\n```\nTOUPET FUNDOPLICATION\n═════════════════════\n\nSteps 1-3 same as Nissen (dissection, mobilization, crural closure)\n\nFUNDOPLICATION:\n                        ┌─────────────┐\n                        │  Esophagus  │\n                        │      │      │\n                    ╱───┘      │      └───╲\n                   │           │           │\n                   │    270°   │    wrap   │\n                   │           │           │\n                    ╲──────────┴──────────╱\n                            │\n                         Stomach\n\nConstruction:\n1. Pass fundus POSTERIOR to esophagus\n2. Suture fundus to LEFT crus (2-3 sutures)\n3. Suture fundus to LEFT esophageal wall\n4. Suture fundus to RIGHT crus (2-3 sutures)\n5. Suture fundus to RIGHT esophageal wall\n6. Creates 270° posterior wrap\n7. Anterior esophagus remains free (90° gap)\n\nAdvantages:\n• Less dysphagia than Nissen\n• Maintains ability to belch/vomit\n• Good for weak peristalsis\n• Effective reflux control (85-90%)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Special Situations\n\n### Large Paraesophageal Hernia\n\n```\nPARAESOPHAGEAL HERNIA REPAIR\n════════════════════════════\n\nKEY PRINCIPLES:\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                                                       │\n│  1. COMPLETE REDUCTION                               │\n│     • Reduce all herniated contents                  │\n│     • Excise hernia sac (controversial)             │\n│                                                       │\n│  2. ADEQUATE ESOPHAGEAL LENGTH                       │\n│     • Need ≥2-3 cm intra-abdominal esophagus        │\n│     • If short → Collis gastroplasty                │\n│                                                       │\n│  3. CRURAL REPAIR                                    │\n│     • Primary closure if possible                   │\n│     • Mesh reinforcement for large defects          │\n│     • Biologic > Synthetic (erosion risk)          │\n│                                                       │\n│  4. FUNDOPLICATION                                   │\n│     • Anchors stomach below diaphragm               │\n│     • Nissen or Toupet based on motility           │\n│                                                       │\n│  5. GASTROPEXY (optional)                           │\n│     • Fixes stomach to anterior abdominal wall     │\n│     • Reduces recurrence                             │\n│                                                       │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Short Esophagus - Collis Gastroplasty\n\n```\nCOLLIS GASTROPLASTY\n═══════════════════\n\nIndication: Short esophagus (<2 cm intra-abdominal)\n\nTechnique:\n\n    Normal                    After Collis\n    ───────                   ────────────\n\n        │                          │\n        │                          │\n    ════╪════ Diaphragm       ════╪════\n        │                          │\n    ┌───┴───┐                  │   │\n    │       │                  │   │ ← Neo-esophagus\n    │Stomach│              ┌───┴───┴───┐\n    │       │              │           │\n    └───────┘              │  Stomach  │\n                           │           │\n                           └───────────┘\n\n• Stapled division of proximal stomach\n• Creates 3-5 cm \"neo-esophagus\"\n• Allows tension-free wrap below diaphragm\n• Fundoplication around neo-esophagus\n```\n\n### Mesh in Hiatal Repair\n\n| Factor | Consideration |\n|--------|---------------|\n| When to use | Large defect (>5 cm), recurrent hernia |\n| Mesh type | Biologic preferred (lower erosion) |\n| Placement | Onlay reinforcement, not bridging |\n| Controversy | Mixed evidence on recurrence benefit |\n| Complications | Mesh erosion into esophagus (rare but serious) |\n\n---\n\n## Outcomes and Complications\n\n### Expected Outcomes\n\n```\nFUNDOPLICATION OUTCOMES\n═══════════════════════\n\nSUCCESS RATES (symptom control):\n─────────────────────────────────────────────────\n                    Short-term    Long-term\n                    (1-2 years)   (5-10 years)\n─────────────────────────────────────────────────\nHeartburn relief    90-95%        80-85%\nRegurgitation       95%           85-90%\nOverall satisfaction 85-90%       75-85%\n─────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nFUNCTIONAL OUTCOMES:\n─────────────────────────────────────────────────\nDysphagia (early)           30-50% (transient)\nDysphagia (persistent)      3-5%\nBloating                    10-15%\nInability to vomit          5-10%\nPPI discontinuation         70-80%\n─────────────────────────────────────────────────\n```\n\n### Complications\n\n```\nCOMPLICATIONS OF FUNDOPLICATION\n═══════════════════════════════\n\nINTRAOPERATIVE:\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ • Esophageal/gastric perforation (1-2%)         │\n│ • Splenic injury (0.5-1%)                        │\n│ • Pneumothorax (1-2%)                           │\n│ • Vagal nerve injury (rare)                     │\n│ • Bleeding                                       │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nEARLY POSTOPERATIVE:\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ • Dysphagia (common, usually resolves)          │\n│ • Bloating/gas-bloat syndrome                   │\n│ • Diarrhea (vagal injury)                       │\n│ • Wrap disruption/leak                          │\n│ • Pulmonary complications                        │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nLATE:\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ • Recurrent reflux (10-15%)                     │\n│ • Wrap herniation (5-10%)                       │\n│ • Wrap disruption (slipped Nissen)             │\n│ • Persistent dysphagia                          │\n│ • Paraesophageal hernia                         │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### \"Slipped\" Nissen\n\n```\nSLIPPED NISSEN FUNDOPLICATION\n═════════════════════════════\n\nNormal Wrap:              Slipped Wrap:\n\n    │                          │\n    │                          │\n┌───┴───┐                     │\n│ Wrap  │               ┌─────┴─────┐\n│       │               │   Wrap    │\n│  EGJ  │               │           │\n│       │               │   Stomach │ ← Stomach\n└───────┘               │   hernia- │   above wrap\n    │                   │   ted     │\n Stomach                └───────────┘\n                             │\n                          Stomach\n\nCauses:\n• Wrap not secured to esophagus\n• Wrap too loose\n• Inadequate crural repair\n• Poor tissue quality\n\nSymptoms:\n• Recurrent reflux\n• Dysphagia\n• Early satiety\n• Epigastric pain\n\nManagement:\n• Re-do fundoplication\n• May need conversion to Toupet\n```\n\n---\n\n## Alternative/Emerging Procedures\n\n### Magnetic Sphincter Augmentation (LINX)\n\n```\nLINX DEVICE\n═══════════\n\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                                              │\n│  Device: Ring of titanium beads with        │\n│          magnetic cores                      │\n│                                              │\n│      ┌─○─○─○─○─○─○─○─○─┐                    │\n│      │                 │  ← Magnetic ring   │\n│      └─────────────────┘    around LES      │\n│                                              │\n│  Mechanism:                                  │\n│  • Magnets attract = closed sphincter       │\n│  • Swallowing overcomes magnets = opens     │\n│  • Allows burp/vomit (unlike tight Nissen)  │\n│                                              │\n│  Outcomes:                                   │\n│  • 85-90% symptom relief                    │\n│  • Less dysphagia than Nissen               │\n│  • Less gas-bloat                           │\n│                                              │\n│  Concerns:                                   │\n│  • MRI compatibility (newer versions OK)    │\n│  • Device erosion (rare)                    │\n│  • Long-term data limited                   │\n│  • Cost                                      │\n│                                              │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Transoral Incisionless Fundoplication (TIF)\n\n| Aspect | Details |\n|--------|---------|\n| Approach | Endoscopic (no incisions) |\n| Mechanism | Creates 2-3 cm valve at EGJ |\n| Device | EsophyX device |\n| Efficacy | 60-70% (lower than surgical) |\n| Best for | Small hiatal hernia (<2 cm), mild GERD |\n| Limitations | Cannot address large hernia |\n\n### Roux-en-Y Gastric Bypass for GERD\n\n**When to consider:**\n- Morbid obesity + GERD\n- Failed fundoplication in obese patient\n- Barrett''s esophagus in obese patient\n\n**Advantages:**\n- Addresses both obesity and GERD\n- Excellent reflux control\n- May improve Barrett''s\n\n---\n\n## Redo Surgery\n\n### Indications for Reoperation\n\n```\nINDICATIONS FOR REDO FUNDOPLICATION\n═══════════════════════════════════\n\n1. ANATOMIC FAILURE\n   • Wrap herniation\n   • Wrap disruption\n   • Slipped Nissen\n   • Twisted/malpositioned wrap\n\n2. FUNCTIONAL FAILURE\n   • Recurrent reflux (confirmed on pH study)\n   • Too-tight wrap (persistent dysphagia)\n\n3. NEW PATHOLOGY\n   • Development of paraesophageal hernia\n   • Esophageal stricture\n\nWORKUP BEFORE REDO:\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ • Detailed symptom history                   │\n│ • EGD (anatomy, esophagitis, Barrett''s)     │\n│ • Barium swallow (wrap position, hernia)    │\n│ • HRM (rule out motility disorder)          │\n│ • pH/impedance (confirm ongoing reflux)     │\n│ • Gastric emptying if indicated             │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Redo Surgery Principles\n\n| Principle | Rationale |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| Complete takedown | Must fully dismantle old wrap |\n| Re-assess esophageal length | May need Collis |\n| Consider partial wrap | Toupet if Nissen failed |\n| Thorough crural repair | Often needs mesh |\n| Higher complication rate | 10-15% vs 2-3% primary |\n\n---\n\n## Key Points for Examination\n\n### Must-Know Facts\n\n```\n╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗\n║                    HIGH-YIELD FACTS                         ║\n╠════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╣\n║                                                             ║\n║  1. INDICATIONS require objective reflux confirmation      ║\n║     • pH study before surgery if EGD normal                ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  2. HRM is ESSENTIAL preoperatively                        ║\n║     • Rule out achalasia (would be wrong surgery!)         ║\n║     • Assess peristalsis → guides wrap choice              ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  3. NISSEN (360°) for normal motility                     ║\n║     TOUPET (270°) for weak motility (IEM)                 ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  4. FLOPPY NISSEN principles:                              ║\n║     • Short (2-3 cm)                                       ║\n║     • Tension-free (divide short gastrics)                │\n║     • Calibrated (50-56 Fr bougie)                        ║\n║     • Fundus-to-fundus                                     ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  5. CRURAL REPAIR is essential                             ║\n║     • Prevents wrap herniation                             ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  6. SHORT ESOPHAGUS → Collis gastroplasty                  ║\n║                                                             ║\n║  7. DYSPHAGIA is common early (30-50%)                    ║\n║     • Usually resolves in 3-6 months                      ║\n║     • Persistent >3 months = evaluate                     ║\n║                                                             ║\n╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝\n```\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n1. Stefanidis D, et al. SAGES Guidelines for Surgical Treatment of GERD. Surg Endosc 2021.\n2. Katz PO, et al. ACG Clinical Guideline: Diagnosis and Management of GERD. Am J Gastroenterol 2022.\n3. Dallemagne B, et al. Laparoscopic Nissen Fundoplication: 20-year Follow-up. Ann Surg 2006.\n4. Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 8th Ed - Chapters 25-35.\n\n---\n\n## Navigation\n\n**Related Notes:**\n- [[Esophageal Motility Disorders]] - Pre-op workup\n- [[03 Spaces/🔬 Active Projects/Learning Modules/Learning System/Study Library/02 - Concept Notes/Esophagus/Achalasia Cardia]] - Important differential\n- [[Achalasia - LHM vs POEM]] - Fundoplication in myotomy\n\n**Study Materials:**\n- [[GRINDE Map - Surgical Management of GERD]]\n- [[Retrieval Cards - Surgical Management of GERD]]\n- [[Case - GERD Surgical Evaluation]]\n\n---\n*Last updated: January 2026 | Teaching Roster Topic #21*","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
