  '{"markdown":"# Zenker Diverticulum\n\n> **Source**: Shackelford Ch 5 - *Pharyngoesophageal (Zenker''s) Diverticulum*, Ch 6 - *Other Esophageal Diverticula*, Ch 18\n> **Topic System**: [[Esophagus Index]]\n> **Phase**: Shoot\n> **Tier**: 3 (Pathology)\n\n---\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n> [!summary] One-liner\n> Zenker diverticulum is a FALSE (pulsion) diverticulum arising posteriorly through Killian''s dehiscence (between thyropharyngeus and cricopharyngeus) due to UES dysfunction, presenting with dysphagia, regurgitation of undigested food, and halitosis—treated by cricopharyngeal myotomy ± diverticulectomy or pexy.\n\n---\n\n## Anatomy and Pathophysiology\n\n### Location: Killian''s Dehiscence\n\n```\n    KILLIAN''S DEHISCENCE - SITE OF ZENKER''S\n    ═══════════════════════════════════════\n\n    Posterior View of Pharyngoesophageal Junction:\n\n                    Pharynx\n                      │\n         ┌────────────┴────────────┐\n         │                         │\n         │   THYROPHARYNGEUS       │ ← Inferior pharyngeal\n         │   (oblique fibers)      │   constrictor (upper)\n         │                         │\n         ├─────────────────────────┤\n         │ ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░ │ ← KILLIAN''S DEHISCENCE\n         │ ░░░ Weak point ░░░░░░░░ │   (No muscle - only mucosa)\n         ├─────────────────────────┤\n         │                         │\n         │   CRICOPHARYNGEUS       │ ← Inferior pharyngeal\n         │   (transverse fibers)   │   constrictor (lower)\n         │   = UES                 │\n         │                         │\n         └────────────┬────────────┘\n                      │\n                  Esophagus\n\n\n    LATERAL VIEW - Diverticulum Formation:\n\n         Thyropharyngeus\n              ╲\n               ╲\n                ╲  ┌──────────┐\n                 ╲ │ ZENKER''s │ ← Pouch herniates\n                  ╲│          │   POSTERIORLY\n                   ├──────────┤   through Killian''s\n                   │░░░░░░░░░░│\n                   │CRICOPHAR.│ ← UES (often dysfunctional)\n                   └──────────┘\n                       │\n                   Esophagus\n```\n\n### Pathophysiology\n\n```\n    ZENKER''S FORMATION MECHANISM\n    ════════════════════════════\n\n    UES (Cricopharyngeus) Dysfunction\n                │\n                ▼\n    Incomplete/Delayed relaxation during swallow\n                │\n                ▼\n    Increased intrapharyngeal pressure\n                │\n                ▼\n    Pressure transmitted to weak point (Killian''s)\n                │\n                ▼\n    Mucosal herniation POSTERIORLY\n                │\n                ▼\n    Progressive enlargement over time\n                │\n                ▼\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │           ZENKER DIVERTICULUM               │\n    │                                             │\n    │   • FALSE diverticulum (mucosa only)        │\n    │   • PULSION type (pushed out)              │\n    │   • Location: Posterior, midline            │\n    │   • Triangular \"Killian''s dehiscence\"       │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Types of Esophageal Diverticula - Classification\n\n| Type | Location | Mechanism | True/False | Example |\n|------|----------|-----------|------------|---------|\n| **Pharyngoesophageal** | Above UES | Pulsion | FALSE | Zenker |\n| **Midesophageal** | Middle 1/3 | Traction | Usually TRUE | TB, histoplasmosis |\n| **Epiphrenic** | Above LES | Pulsion | FALSE | Associated with dysmotility |\n\n---\n\n## Clinical Presentation\n\n### Symptoms\n\n```\n    ZENKER''S CLINICAL PRESENTATION\n    ═══════════════════════════════\n\n    CLASSIC TRIAD\n    ─────────────\n    1. DYSPHAGIA (90%+)\n       • Progressive over years\n       • Solids > liquids initially\n       • Worse as pouch enlarges\n\n    2. REGURGITATION OF UNDIGESTED FOOD (75%)\n       • Hours after eating\n       • Food NOT mixed with acid/bile\n       • Often occurs when lying down\n       • \"Food from yesterday\"\n\n    3. HALITOSIS (50%+)\n       • From retained, decomposing food\n       • May be socially distressing\n\n    ADDITIONAL SYMPTOMS\n    ───────────────────\n    • Neck mass/gurgling (Boyce sign)\n    • Aspiration/recurrent pneumonia\n    • Nocturnal coughing\n    • Weight loss (in severe cases)\n    • Voice changes (compression)\n```\n\n### Physical Examination\n\n| Finding | Significance |\n|---------|--------------|\n| **Boyce sign** | Gurgling in neck with palpation |\n| **Neck mass** | Visible/palpable in large diverticula |\n| **Pulmonary crackles** | Aspiration pneumonitis |\n| **Weight loss** | Poor oral intake |\n\n### Risk Factors\n\n| Factor | Notes |\n|--------|-------|\n| **Age** | Typically >60 years (7th-8th decade) |\n| **Sex** | Male predominance |\n| **UES dysfunction** | Primary pathology |\n| **GERD** | May contribute to UES dysfunction |\n\n---\n\n## Diagnosis\n\n### Diagnostic Studies\n\n```\n    DIAGNOSTIC APPROACH\n    ═══════════════════\n\n    FIRST LINE: BARIUM SWALLOW (Video fluoroscopy)\n    ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n    • Diagnostic study of choice\n    • Shows: Posterior outpouching above UES\n    • Demonstrates size and location\n    • Can see food retention\n    • Safe (no perforation risk)\n\n         ┌─────────────────────────┐\n         │                         │\n         │    ┌────────┐           │\n         │    │ Pouch  │◄──────────│── Barium fills\n         │    │(Zenker)│           │   diverticulum\n         │    └───┬────┘           │\n         │        │                │\n         │    ════╪════ ◄──────────│── UES (cricopharyngeus)\n         │        │                │\n         │    Esophagus            │\n         └─────────────────────────┘\n\n    SECOND LINE: EGD (with CAUTION)\n    ────────────────────────────────\n    • Risk of entering diverticulum → PERFORATION\n    • Should be done by experienced endoscopist\n    • Enter with scope positioned anteriorly\n    • Useful for: Cancer screening, associated pathology\n\n    OPTIONAL: CT Neck/Chest\n    ───────────────────────\n    • If concern for malignancy\n    • Aspiration pneumonia workup\n    • Pre-operative planning\n```\n\n### Barium Swallow Findings\n\n| Finding | Description |\n|---------|-------------|\n| **Posterior outpouching** | Above cricopharyngeus |\n| **Barium retention** | In dependent portion |\n| **\"Shelf\" sign** | At cricopharyngeus level |\n| **Aspiration** | Into airway (if observed) |\n| **Size measurement** | Guides surgical approach |\n\n### Size Classification\n\n| Size | Description | Surgical Implication |\n|------|-------------|---------------------|\n| **Small** | <2 cm | Myotomy alone may suffice |\n| **Medium** | 2-4 cm | Myotomy + diverticulopexy |\n| **Large** | >4-6 cm | Myotomy + diverticulectomy |\n\n---\n\n## Treatment\n\n### Principles of Treatment\n\n```\n    TREATMENT PRINCIPLES\n    ════════════════════\n\n    KEY INSIGHT: The PRIMARY problem is UES dysfunction\n                (cricopharyngeal muscle)\n\n    Therefore: CRICOPHARYNGEAL MYOTOMY is ESSENTIAL\n              in ALL surgical approaches\n\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                                                 │\n    │  Myotomy ALONE ──► Small diverticula (<2 cm)   │\n    │                                                 │\n    │  Myotomy + PEXY ──► Medium diverticula          │\n    │  (tack pouch up)                               │\n    │                                                 │\n    │  Myotomy + ECTOMY ──► Large diverticula        │\n    │  (resect pouch)                                │\n    │                                                 │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n    WITHOUT myotomy = HIGH RECURRENCE RATE\n```\n\n### Surgical Options\n\n#### 1. Open Transcervical Approach (Traditional)\n\n```\n    OPEN CRICOPHARYNGEAL MYOTOMY + DIVERTICULECTOMY\n    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════\n\n    APPROACH:\n    • Left neck incision (anterior to SCM)\n    • Diverticulum found posteriorly\n    • Retract thyroid, carotid laterally\n\n    STEPS:\n    ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n    │                                                 │\n    │  1. Identify diverticulum                       │\n    │                                                 │\n    │  2. Dissect to neck of pouch                    │\n    │                                                 │\n    │  3. MYOTOMY of cricopharyngeus                  │\n    │     • Extend 3-4 cm onto esophagus              │\n    │     • Include ALL circular fibers               │\n    │                                                 │\n    │  4. Address diverticulum:                       │\n    │     • Small: Myotomy alone                      │\n    │     • Medium: Pexy (tack superiorly)            │\n    │     • Large: Excise with stapler                │\n    │                                                 │\n    │  5. Drain placement (optional)                  │\n    │                                                 │\n    └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n    MYOTOMY DIAGRAM:\n    ────────────────\n\n         ║           ╔══════════════╗\n         ║   Pouch   ║              ║\n         ║     ◄─────║              ║\n         ║           ╠══════════════╣\n         ║        ───║──────────────║─── MYOTOMY\n         ║           ║ Cricophar.   ║    (divide)\n         ║           ╠══════════════╣\n         ║           ║   Esophagus  ║\n         ║           ╚══════════════╝\n```\n\n#### 2. Endoscopic Approach (Minimally Invasive)\n\n```\n    ENDOSCOPIC CRICOPHARYNGEAL MYOTOMY\n    ══════════════════════════════════\n\n    TECHNIQUES:\n    ───────────\n\n    1. RIGID ENDOSCOPY (Dohlman procedure)\n       • Bivalve laryngoscope exposes septum\n       • CO2 laser or stapler divides septum\n       • Septum = common wall between pouch and esophagus\n       • Dividing septum = opens pouch + performs myotomy\n\n    2. FLEXIBLE ENDOSCOPY (Z-POEM, peroral)\n       • Similar to POEM for achalasia\n       • Submucosal tunnel to cricopharyngeus\n       • Myotomy from inside\n       • Newer technique\n\n    SEPTUM DIVISION:\n    ────────────────\n\n         ┌───────────────────────┐\n         │       Pouch           │\n         │         │             │\n         │    ═════╪═════        │ ← Septum (common wall)\n         │         │             │   DIVIDE THIS\n         │      Esophagus        │\n         └───────────────────────┘\n\n                    │\n                    ▼ After division\n\n         ┌───────────────────────┐\n         │                       │\n         │    ╔═══════════╗      │\n         │    ║           ║      │ ← Wide opening\n         │    ║  Single   ║      │   Pouch drains into\n         │    ║  lumen    ║      │   esophagus\n         │    ╚═══════════╝      │\n         └───────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Comparison of Approaches\n\n| Feature | Open | Endoscopic |\n|---------|------|------------|\n| **Anesthesia** | General | General |\n| **Hospital stay** | 2-3 days | 0-1 days |\n| **Diet resumption** | POD 1-2 | Same day |\n| **Success rate** | 90-95% | 85-95% |\n| **Recurrence** | 3-5% | 10-15% |\n| **Complications** | Wound, RLN injury, leak | Perforation, mediastinitis |\n| **Best for** | Large diverticula | Small-medium, poor surgical candidates |\n| **Repeat procedure** | Difficult | Can repeat |\n\n### Surgical Complications\n\n| Complication | Incidence | Prevention/Management |\n|--------------|-----------|----------------------|\n| **Recurrence** | 3-15% | Adequate myotomy length |\n| **Leak/fistula** | 1-5% | Meticulous closure, drain |\n| **Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury** | 1-3% | Careful dissection |\n| **Mediastinitis** | 1-2% | Early recognition, drainage |\n| **Stricture** | 2-5% | Avoid excessive resection |\n| **Hematoma** | 1-2% | Hemostasis, drain |\n\n---\n\n## Post-operative Care\n\n### Standard Protocol\n\n| Timeframe | Management |\n|-----------|------------|\n| **POD 0** | NPO, IV fluids |\n| **POD 1** | Gastrografin swallow (if performed diverticulectomy) |\n| **POD 1-2** | Clear liquids if swallow negative |\n| **POD 2-3** | Soft diet, consider discharge |\n| **Week 1-2** | Soft diet at home |\n| **Week 2+** | Regular diet |\n\n### Follow-up\n\n- Clinical assessment at 2-4 weeks\n- Repeat barium swallow only if symptoms recur\n- Long-term success: >90%\n\n---\n\n## Special Considerations\n\n### Zenker and Esophageal Cancer\n\n- Squamous cell carcinoma can arise IN diverticulum\n- Incidence: 0.5-1% of Zenker diverticula\n- Long-standing, untreated pouches at higher risk\n- EGD recommended to inspect pouch mucosa\n\n### Zenker vs Other Diverticula\n\n```\n    ESOPHAGEAL DIVERTICULA COMPARISON\n    ══════════════════════════════════\n\n                ZENKER           MID-ESOPHAGEAL      EPIPHRENIC\n                ──────           ──────────────      ──────────\n\n    Location    Pharyngo-        Middle third        Distal 10 cm\n                esophageal                           (above LES)\n\n    Type        FALSE            TRUE (usually)      FALSE\n                (pulsion)        (traction)          (pulsion)\n\n    Cause       UES              TB, histoplasma,    Motility\n                dysfunction      mediastinal LN      disorder\n                                                     (achalasia, DES)\n\n    Wall        Mucosa only      All layers          Mucosa only\n\n    Treatment   Myotomy +        Usually observe     Myotomy +\n                diverticulectomy or treat cause      diverticulectomy\n                                                     + treat motility\n```\n\n### Cricopharyngeal Bar\n\n```\n    CRICOPHARYNGEAL BAR (ACHALASIA OF UES)\n    ═══════════════════════════════════════\n\n    • Prominent cricopharyngeus muscle on barium swallow\n    • May occur WITHOUT diverticulum\n    • Same pathophysiology (UES dysfunction)\n    • Can progress to Zenker if untreated\n\n    Treatment: Cricopharyngeal myotomy\n               (Botox can be tried first)\n\n    BARIUM IMAGE:\n    ─────────────\n\n         ┌─────────────────┐\n         │     Pharynx     │\n         │                 │\n         │    ▬▬▬▬▬▬▬▬▬    │ ← \"Bar\" = indentation\n         │        │        │   from hypertrophied\n         │    Esophagus    │   cricopharyngeus\n         └─────────────────┘\n```\n\n---\n\n## Connections\n\n### Links to Other Concepts\n\n- **Related anatomy**: [[Esophageal Anatomy]] (UES, pharynx)\n- **Differential of dysphagia**: [[03 Spaces/🔬 Active Projects/Learning Modules/Learning System/Study Library/02 - Concept Notes/Esophagus/Achalasia Cardia]] (LES problem), [[GERD]] with stricture\n- **Similar mechanism**: Epiphrenic diverticulum (pulsion, distal)\n- **Motility assessment**: [[Esophageal Manometry]]\n\n---\n\n## Quick Recall Questions\n\n1. Q: Where exactly does Zenker diverticulum form?\n   A: Through Killian''s dehiscence - the weak point BETWEEN thyropharyngeus (above) and cricopharyngeus (below)\n\n2. Q: Why is cricopharyngeal myotomy essential in Zenker surgery?\n   A: The PRIMARY pathology is UES (cricopharyngeal) dysfunction. Without myotomy, recurrence rate is high because the underlying cause is not addressed.\n\n3. Q: What is Boyce sign?\n   A: Gurgling sound in the neck when the Zenker diverticulum is palpated (retained air/fluid in pouch)\n\n4. Q: What distinguishes Zenker (pharyngoesophageal) from mid-esophageal diverticula?\n   A: Zenker is FALSE (mucosa only) and PULSION type; mid-esophageal is usually TRUE (all layers) and TRACTION type (from external inflammation like TB)\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Shackelford Ch 5: *Pharyngoesophageal (Zenker''s) Diverticulum*\n- Shackelford Ch 6: *Other Esophageal Diverticula*\n- Shackelford Ch 18: *Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction*\n\n---\n\n*VPReFRE Checklist:*\n- [x] **V**isual: Anatomy diagrams, surgical technique\n- [x] **P**rocessed: Pathophysiology explained\n- [x] **Re**lational: Compared to other diverticula\n- [x] **R**eflective: Treatment decision-making\n- [x] **E**fficient: Focused content","format":"markdown"}'::jsonb,
